Thanks Sean for the detailed explanation.

I had a discussion with Sdague about this patch on IRC and his opinion was that this test-case
is not a valid test-case i.e., it does not really validate the Gateway creation as the subnet 
information is only stored in the neutron db. He was suggesting that we enhance the patch/test-case 
to check that Gateway ip is actually configured to the port on attaching the subnet to the router.

Now keeping in view of your thoughts that 
a. the Gateway-IP (even if its a LLA) will be specified only when using an external router (i.e, provider n/w scenario)
b. there is a plan to populate/override the gateway attribute of the subnet in router attachment step (i.e., Neutron router is used)
I'm a bit confused on how to proceed with the patch. 

IMHO, following are the possibilities.
1. Modify the patch to use a LLA as the GW ip. But this would not be inline with the Bug#1318962 description. 
   Not only that, we also have a separate patch that addresses the LLA use-case - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/93483. 
   So LLA use-case would be covered in that patch.
2. Even though, specifying the GW ip outside of subnet CIDR (i.e., LLA or GUA) is meaningful only in a provider network scenario,
   since Neutron allows subnet creation with GW ip part of Subnet CIDR, we can enhance the patch as per the suggestions from sdague 
   (i.e, create Neutron router, attach router interface to the subnet and check that port is configured 
   with Gateway IP specified in subnet). This may fail once option b above is implemented. 
3. Remove the current test-case from tempest as its not a valid use-case. 
4. Merge the patch in the current state as it addresses the issue of hardcoding. 

Any suggestions or thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-04 09:31:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
Fix hardcoded gateway in IPV6 subnet api tests

This patch removes the hardcoding and calculates the Gateway-ip
based on the tenant_network_v6_cidr value.

Change-Id: Iee4c450714caf49d6753d9455e6ab3698b64340d
Closes-Bug: #1318962

commit_message:
Adding support of DNS nameserver and Host routes for the Nuage Plugin

This commit will implement the following DHCP options:
 - DNS nameserver
 - Host routes

Implements: blueprint dhcp-host-routes-and-dns-support-for-nuage-plugin
Change-Id: Idbb04f46112cddd588cad88921210aa0f63645f6

commit_message:
Change v3 attach_interface to v2.1

This patch changes v3 attach_interface API to v2.1 and makes v2
unit tests share between v2 and v2.1.

The differences between v2 and v3 are described on the wiki page
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: If18676604edc8fea41d7888eb6546245163e91c2

commit_message:
Clean up shell display of slave info

Suppress links and improve display of slave information for the 'show' and
'create' commands. Also refactor shell.py to avoid repeating the code for
displaying an instance.

The revised print_instance method also avoids bug 1322822 where the order
in which attributes are queried can affect the display output.

Depends-On: If8a154083d0095606fb3ee115cc9b66ab788cbb4

Partially-Implements: blueprint replication-v1
Partial-Bug: 1322822
Change-Id: Ie1ac42d61e920ac8ea1ebab35c2db096fd313077

commit_message:
Support oslo-incubator in final release scripts

Add support for oslo-incubator in rccut.sh and rcdelivery.sh.
Oslo-incubator does not get tarballs generated or uploaded, so we skip
appropriate parts of the script. It also introduces a difference between
LP project name ("oslo") and git repo ("oslo-incubator") that the script
takes into account.

Change-Id: I8fb9f37b6719a8f9187ee12267a687d09e463dae

commit_message:
Check results of one test in run_single_ostf_test

In 'run_single_ostf_test' method we run only one health
check for environment and expect that it will pass. So
we should verify only its results, because some other OSTF
tests ould fail earlier.

Change-Id: Ibb0d38a10fda4f1250b78e7fb61dd66bdc4505d6
Closes-bug: #1354300

commit_message:
Fix MemcachedKeyCharacterError when keys have spaces

Apparently memcached protocol uses a text based protocol
where spaces are significant. Hence there is a well known
bug that the keys should not have spaces or control characters
in them. In this review, we just add a decorator to "fixup"
any keys to prevent this problem.

Change-Id: I57c80b5807c0dd92dd716812cf1f98726686f6da

commit_message:
Make the catalog flavor-aware

This patch adds the knowledge of flavors to the catalog. When a new
queue is registered, if a flavor is passed, it'll get the pool from the
flavor record. If flavor is not passed, it'll preserve the previous
behavior.

Partially Implements blueprint: marconi-queue-flavors

Change-Id: Idcf5a0215699269f29df793169ff21fc6435f3b2

I like it, this is definitely easier to understand and I think it makes sense to move the options to the "details" tab. Am I correct to assume the default ("Address from non OpenStack service") is likely to work in most cases?

If the default is not really guaranteed to get the user a working setup, maybe it would make sense to have something like "Select one" as the default to force people to look through the options (though it's still difficult to choose!). Is there a docs page somewhere that we could link to (or copy from :)) to help people make a more informed decision?'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-08-28 15:12:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thanks Julie for your comments. I totally agree with you that we should have the appropriate default selection. I will confirm what is the *good* default  to asking IPv6 Neutron side.

I have another concern on the current Neutron API that exposing two IPv6 attributes are too specific to operators and I am afraid users are confused. It is being under discussion. It might be hard to fix it in Juno timeframe. On the other hand, IPv6 full support is one of the important topics in Neutron and it is worth supported in Horizon. Choosing better default option would help us and users.'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-08-28 15:14:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Support Neutron IPv6 RA/address modes

IPv6 RA mode and IPv6 address mode were added to Neutron to allow
users to control how IPv6 address and additional info to VMs.

Implements blueprint neutron-subnet-mode-support

Change-Id: I69ccf49ffbe6025e937594556add7822fda27520

commit_message:
Added amqplib>=1.0.2 package to the global-requirements

While deploying OpenStack through devstack, when
global-requirements.txt tries to sync with /opt/stack/cinder/requirements.txt.
the devstack installation fails saying 'amqplib' is not in
global-requirements.txt

Closes-Bug: #1343838

Change-Id: Id0a6cda55b697032193fb04a56f3e63baba28710

commit_message:
Change 'image_ref'/'flavor_ref' into v2 style for servers

This patch changes 'image_ref'/'flavor_ref' to 'imageRef'/'flavorRef'
that same with v2 api. And also change the related unittest.
The differences between v2 and v3 are described on the wiki page

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Ic17334e0a9de89488d5e0c8b75950027d51a3cd4

commit_message:
Improve help strings

Make help strings consistent:
* Add missing spaces between words
* Capitalize first word of help
* Add "." at end of string
* Improve wording and capitalization

This follows the oslo.config style guide:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.config/styleguide.html

Change-Id: I8243909249423b6b58ccda0d800856f46b0953c5

commit_message:
Change v3 extended_server_attibutes to v2.1

This patch changes v3 extended_server_attibutes API to v2.1 and makes v2
unit tests share between v2 and v2.1.
Revert v3 changes back to v2.
os-extended-server-attributes:* -> OS-EXT-SRV-ATTR:*
The differences between v2 and v3 are described on the wiki page
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I02b203b62b9e675f71d0ff3880bc9ee051a3b80d

(2 comments)

I really like this patch, especially the use of AST. I have other hacking checks that I think I can easily implement on top of that base support.

Should we forbid unicode() as well in lieu of six.text_type()? This might be better as a followup for Py3 support.'}, {'account_id': 6601, 'date': '2014-08-21 19:11:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Johannes take a look at the dependent patch: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/116055.  I added a helper such that the code to check for use of unicode() would require a subclass with one method: 

    def visit_Call(self, node):
        if self._check_call_names(node, ['unicode']):
            self.add_error(node.args[0])
        super(CheckForUnicodeOp, self).generic_visit(node)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-21 21:10:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Remove use of str on exceptions

An exception's message can be a translatable message.  If it is, the message
can contain unicode characters which will cause str to fail.

In cases where the message is explicity needed, the use of str is replaced
with the use of six.text_type.  When an exception is used as a replacement
string in a format string, the logger correctly handles it without the
need for str, so it is removed.

In addition to the case where a translatable message contains unicode,
enabling lazy translation in the oslo.i18n library causes translatable
messages to be replaced with an object that does not support str, this
causes all calls to str on a translatable message to fail.  Thus this patch
is also needed to support blueprint: i18n-enablement.

This patch includes a hacking check for use of str() on exceptions identified
in except statements.

Change-Id: Idb426d7f710ea69b835f70d0e883e93e9b9111d2
Partially-Implements: blueprint i18n-enablement

commit_message:
Remove wording advising against certain wsgi services

Rather than advise against certain services, this will stick with just
recommending specific services and not mentioning the others.

Change-Id: I2600f210ddc1b0b02daecaa61c6bab489a1db017
Closes-Bug: 1362748

commit_message:
Move sahara client installation to lib/sahara

All other projects installs their clients in the same lib file as the
main services.

Remove sahara-dashboard installation

Sahara dashboard is now merged into the Horizon and enabled by default
(when data_processing endpoint is available), so, we should stop
installing it as separated dashboard.

commit_message:
Change 'admin_password' into v2 style for servers extension

This patch changes 'admin_password' to 'adminPass' that same
with v2 api. And also change the related unittest.

The differences between v2 and v3 are described on the wiki page
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Ie5675f98bb15c55a191a207171e2ffe3be8e6deb

commit_message:
Don't set tunnel_types on VLAN network type

The current code sets tunnel types for the neutron agent
even when the network type is 'vlan'. This results in the
agent not starting because 'vlan' is not a valid tunnel type.
This patch changes it so tunnel_types is not populated when
vlans are used.

This bug just now surfaced because of commit
8feaf6c9516094df58df84479d73779e87a79264 requiring Q_ML2_TENANT_NETWORK_TYPE
to be set to avoid being set to the 'local' type.

Conflicts:
	lib/neutron_plugins/ml2

Change-Id: I0649c8a8bd8fe55f743481e447867faf12b8b542
(cherry picked from commit e3cfbf1580d4e0b77191a2f4bcb61bde9f8d9815)

commit_message:
Change ViewBuilder into v2.1 for servers

This patch changes v3 servers' ViewBuilder to v2.1. And also
change related unittests and api sample tests.

The differences between v2 and v3 are described on the wiki page
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Ie68d46daa91ef43c84eeef479c0986d5e7f15719

commit_message:
Adding comparison operators in query for event traits

In EventFilter we have an optional parameter 'op' in traits_filter part. But up
to date usage of this param has been implemented only in Hbase and
Mongodb backends. However in API we can use only 'op'='eq'.

This change improves usage of parameter 'op' in query for events in api, and
adds possibility to use comparison in query with SQL backend.

Some tests are also added to cover using of this new feature.

Closes-bug: #1354009
Change-Id: I4824800eac7270bcfa10882a735e48d80bf32712

Use lockutils module for tox functional env

A previous change (I4d6076e5f7586a11ea5381f18774d4bab57b0081) added
lockutils to only the dsvm-functional tox env.  It also needs to be
added to the functional tox env.

Closes-Bug: 1332380

Add NetworkRequest object and associated list

This adds a new object to replace the network API's "megatuple"
(aka "tuple-o-doom").

Change-Id: I0e83809ae23ffac1cde9113b61846053da48b0a0

Peter, please note that there is one significant downside with the fix the way you and I are proposing. There are some code paths that already do as this proposed code change is doing.

See ./trove/guestagent/datastore/cassandra/service.py at _get_actual_db_status()

If the change that you and I are proposing were to be implemented, then one would have to go and scour the source base for all exeception handlers for the exception.ProcessExecutionError and remove any logging of stdout and stderr there.

I think that would be better in the long run.

Just to be clear, I see no code in processutils.execute that actually logs stdout and stderr, it throws it as part of an exception though.'}, {'account_id': 8415, 'date': '2014-07-14 13:26:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
show stdout/err from failed command execution

When executing a command the mysql service status command it is useful
to see the actual output of the failing command in debug mode, not just
the exit status.

Add a log_output_on_error parameter to execute_with_timeout() so this
can be reused.

Change-Id: Iff931d0489754303e099e8567bca3237fd476f8f
Closes-Bug: #1340124

commit_message:
Adjusted audit logging for trove.instance module

The trove.instance module is logging some verbose debug data at the
info level, and some info messages at the debug level. Some log
entries are also lacking context because of missing identifiers such
as InstanceID and TenantID.

Changed logging level of various messages to conform to standard,
added references to various ID's as needed.

Change-Id: I3bb569529befa2b2497d2d5a094e3306e569422c
Partial-Bug: #1324206

commit_message:
Have task/flow logging go to a separate log file

To be able to point the taskflow logging at a task log
we need to be able to separate the logs coming from cinder
from the logs coming from taskflow (as well as the listener
that acts as the intermediary between both projects).

To start the process of having a detailed task log
location, add-in a new log setting that can be used for just
this purpose.

This is not the most ideal way of doing this, since it just
provides a sample logging configuration adjustment, but there
does not appear to be a better way (due to how
cinder/openstack/common/logging.py can't be modified or adjusted
with a better option).

Part of blueprint task-logging

Change-Id: I5e3946c71110ee1b923c2258f3a7eb83c358426b

commit_message:
Stop augmenting oslo-incubators default log levels

Thanks to I255a68fc60963386e8fefe65c3ffd269795adbf4, the two modules we
explicitly set log levels for are now in oslo-incubator, so we don't
need the extra code introduced  in
Ib5164a22c5cbfa4f9d881b97bb1f623cd4d2f3f3

Change-Id: Iec7bd35da36135fcaf63a384fa35f849a1319738

Thanks Armando for pursuing this. In the past we have tried to harmonize the resource
states across the services. So I am wondering if creating a new state for just the router/firewall will be disruptive in that regard. I am not objecting to this approach, just thinking loud. If we do agree on introducing this new state across the services, then it's less of an issue.

Another option (again, just brain storming),  is we if equate PENDING_CREATE to the "CREATED" state in the case of the distributed router/firewall.

Regardless, I think we are saying that the tempest tests will have to change slightly.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-26 01:23:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Hi Sumit, I agree with you that all the adv services need to align, and this is a first step, and applies to firewalls; more to follow. As for the choice of labels (eg. PENDING_CREATE vs CREATED); the reason why I chose the introduction of a new state is to ensure we don't allow regressions by relaxing the tempest check (that can be found here: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/116377/)

Cheers,
Armando"}, {'account_id': 490, 'date': '2014-08-27 06:10:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Set firewall state to CREATED when dealing with DVR

When DVR is enabled as a default option for creating routers, firewall
resources will need to have a new initial state, so that reconciliation
can be done once all L3 agents have processed the firewall rules.

The new state has been introduced to preserve API bw compatibility
with centralized routers.

Partial-bug: #1360351
Supports-blueprint: neutron-dvr-fwaas

Change-Id: I53122570dd3a2311eedb24ccd925bcdc9ad4f70c

I am curious if there is a bug within the oslo code. I don't think we need to write a function that wraps synchronized. 

The _get_lock_path function in lockutils seems to be trying to get CONF.lock_path but it isn't working for some reason. I'm wondering if a better fix to this would be to find the root cause."}, {'account_id': 177, 'date': '2014-08-21 13:19:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

After discussion with Valeriy, I still think this could be fixed differently.

My vote is to change how we are using the lock_path kwarg of the synchronized function. Currently, it is interpreted as the absolute path of where to put the lock file and not the relative path (which seems to be what we want). 

For example, here https://github.com/stackforge/manila/blob/7ddc3c49e6380988d2281a9016a65466f920e5da/manila/share/drivers/generic.py#L212

instead of:
@lockutils.synchronized(instance_id, external=True,
                                lock_path="attach_detach_locks")
we do:
@lockutils.synchronized("attach_detach_" + instance_id, external=True)

and I believe then issue will not occur as the synchronized function will then look at CONF.lock_path instead of the kwarg, but this is just my opinion.'}, {'account_id': 7534, 'date': '2014-08-21 13:24:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review-1

Totally agree with Alex.

No need in custom synchronized.
The problem can be solved by proper using synchronized from lockutils.

In case if lock_path is not provided in config and env variable for lock-path is not set we can set value in the code of driver'}, {'account_id': 8851, 'date': '2014-08-22 11:04:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 12.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-22 12:26:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: Verified-1

Changes:
- updated 'synchronized' function wrapper in 'manila.utils' module to consider
  option 'lock_path' from config as base lock path, by default it searches
  for env var 'MANILA_LOCK_PATH' if not set then its value is None.

commit_message:
Updated usage of locks

Changes:
- replaced direct usage of sychronized func from lockutils with local wrapper,
  that provides prefix;
- 'lock_path' is not provided anymore as hardcode, defined 'lock_path'
  in config is expected;
- added MANILA_LOCK_PATH to devstack plugin, to be able to set path
  before installation.

Change-Id: I6518df0a6d32f1021b19a48f928f9ec8b00140b2
Closes-Bug: #1347915

commit_message:
Fix func job hook script permission problems

- The hook script is the wrong place to unstack since
  it needs to run as the stack user with sudo privileges and those
  permissions are removed as part of the devstack-vm-gate.sh script.

- The functional job gate hook script needs to use sudo to
  install the test-only rootwrap filter.

Change-Id: Ib2e5ec016a5a414dd9675328650efb2b39b0e3fe
Related-Bug: #1360658
(cherry-picked from commit 2f7932055247df3ac5ec4783e029cfeda0466f71)

commit_message:
Syncing changes from oslo-incubator policy engine

In this patch, I have copied required changes from oslo-incubator
policy module from commit 0da5de6b548d34300a75f80bf87d6a809c609d2f.

This changes are required for implementation of blueprint
restrict-downloading-images-protected-properties.

blueprint: restrict-downloading-images-protected-properties

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-11 12:58:30.000000000', 'message': "Enable v2.1 API endpoint instead of v3 API

Now we have decided Nova v3 API interfaces are disabled and we will
change v3 interfaces to v2 ones for using v3 infrastractures as v2.1 API.
The big difference between v2 and v3 that v2 API URLs contain project-id
but v3 ones don't contain it.
This patch adds APIRouterV21 to support API URLs containing project-id
and replaces v3 API endpoint with v2.1 API one.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Iee75fbd8951c9f246f68a9c75d762335fa5c4b4b
"}, {'created': '2014-08-12 00:10:23.000000000', 'message': "Add v2.1 API router and endpoint

Now we have decided Nova v3 API interfaces are disabled and we will
change v3 interfaces to v2 ones for using v3 infrastractures as v2.1 API.
The big difference between v2 and v3 that v2 API URLs contain project-id
but v3 ones don't contain it.
This patch adds both an API router and an endpoint of v2.1 API to support
API URLs containing project-id.

This patch does not remove v3 API router and endpoint because v3 API tests
use it now. After moving all v3 code to v2.1, we can remove them.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Iee75fbd8951c9f246f68a9c75d762335fa5c4b4b

commit_message:
Add v2.1 API router and endpoint

Now we have decided Nova v3 API interfaces are disabled and we will
change v3 interfaces to v2 ones for using v3 infrastractures as v2.1 API.
The big difference between v2 and v3 that v2 API URLs contain project-id
but v3 ones don't contain it.
This patch adds both an API router and an endpoint of v2.1 API to support
API URLs containing project-id.

This patch does not remove v3 API router and endpoint because v3 API tests
use it now. After moving all v3 code to v2.1, we can remove them.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Iee75fbd8951c9f246f68a9c75d762335fa5c4b4b

commit_message:
Change 'changes_since'/'changes-since' into v2.1 style for servers

This patch changes 'changes_since' to 'change-since' that same
with v2 api. And also change the related unittest.

The differences between v2 and v3 are described on the wiki page
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: If2a95827965bd6955b01190f2d4dd4fcd9c76dc9

The spec says that the URL may be the Auth URL for the region. Is that the intent for this particular blueprint? What is the client implication here? Will it grow an understanding of this as an Auth URL?'}, {'account_id': 6482, 'date': '2014-08-14 16:42:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@David, maybe auth url isn't the best term. The whole point of the URL in the region is that a cloud admin for acme, can add a service provider as a region (name it beta).

At which point, when a user from acme tries to exchange a token from acme, for a saml assertion (to be presented to beta), the user has to provide a token, and a region.

The saml generation code will grab the url field from the service provider region, and stick that in the saml assertion. Since the saml assertion needs some attributes about where it's going.

for your interest: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/114138/"}, {'account_id': 6482, 'date': '2014-08-19 20:33:35.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-19 20:33:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Update region entries to include URLs

Allow a URL to be associated with a certain region.

implements bp keystone-to-keystone-federation

commit_message:
Backport V3 flavor extraspecs API unit tests to V2

This patch backport some of the V3 flavor extraspecs API unit tests
to V2 unit tests.

V2 flavor extraspecs API does not raise HTTPBadRequest error in case
provided extraspecs key is not string. It raise the TypeError instead.

This patch also correct that and raise HTTPBadRequest in such cases.

Change-Id: If73552943a8aa9b714d6748278311e816ec3daf7

[{'created': '2014-08-12 01:34:49.000000000', 'message': 'WIP: Convert deferred_delete v3 plugin to v2.1 API

Changes required to have v3 plugin natively support the V2.1
API

commit_message:
Convert deferred_delete v3 plugin to v2.1 API

Changes required to have v3 plugin natively support the V2.1
API

The force_delete action is reverted back to forceDelete

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I0b050d3328338923cf05521b9ef5cc3b1c50a586

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-26 18:26:16.000000000', 'message': "Fix error when logging http response with python 3

Python 3 changed the semantics of dict.items() [0], which now returns a
iterable 'view' instead of a list of tuples. This has the repercussion
that you can no longer check for membership of a key using:

    key in dict.items()

This patch simply replaces that check with a test for the key existing
in the dict itself, rather than the items.

[0] http://legacy.python.org/dev/peps/pep-3106/

commit_message:
Fix error when logging http response with python 3

Python 3 changed the semantics of dict.items() [0], which now returns a
iterable 'view' instead of a list of tuples. This has the repercussion
that you can no longer check for membership of a key using:

    key in dict.items()

This patch simply replaces that check with a test for the key existing
in the dict itself, rather than the items.

[0] http://legacy.python.org/dev/peps/pep-3106/

Closes-Bug: 1359880

Change-Id: I7c59b0432725b660c9fa7270cde2e07bf3ea77db

commit_message:
update default_log_levels set by ceilometer

the current log levels are pretty old. update the current list to
extend current default default_log_level defined in oslo-incubator
and adding in stevedore and keystoneclient levels

that is needed in stable/icehouse to allow swift+ceilometer
in devstack and devstack gate (otherwise grenade job, that is
using stable/icehouse devstack, won't pass the gate)

Change-Id: I239645ef641613a994a48f20c0238e76dc9660f2
Partial-Bug: #1294789
(cherry picked from commit 4d864cef5a2c8ec912bda5b208771d3b7c966934)

commit_message:
Fix func job hook script permission problems

- The hook script is the wrong place to unstack since
  it needs to run as the stack user with sudo privileges and those
  permissions are removed as part of the devstack-vm-gate.sh script.

- The functional job gate hook script needs to use sudo to
  install the test-only rootwrap filter.

Change-Id: Ib2e5ec016a5a414dd9675328650efb2b39b0e3fe
Related-Bug: #1360658

commit_message:
remove tools/jenkins

The last non bashate change in this directory was from 2012, which
means I assume nothing down here is useful any more as this is largely
the precursor to devstack-gate.

Remove it for cleanliness reasons and to not confuse people setting
up 3rd party ci.

Change-Id: I54f06c2ff5a49a9f811df07a7cdfda4a675953c8

commit_message:
Do not use auto_schedule_routers to add router to agent

auto_schedule_routers makes a number of DB calls that are
unnecessary as they are already made during the validation
phase of add_router_to_l3_agent. Once the validation is
done, the only business left is to create the binding: this
is what this patch does.

Partial-bug: #1356121

Change-Id: Ia9be998c2b94416bc46ef78415099f0099b08c2a

Thanks Winston for your review!  Made changes in api.py and added a test case for the filter scheduler as you suggested.

Regarding quota for cgsnapshot, since there's already quota for snapshot, it will limit cgsnapshot directly. So if quota for snapshot is 10, when the user tries to create the 11th cgsnapshot, it will error out because of the snapshot quota limit. That's why I didn't add it.

Consistency group can be created without any volumes in it, so it needs a separate quota to control."}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-07-23 23:43:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

I haven't thought it through yet just have a feeling such limit isn't obvious enough. Xing,

The snapshot quota is enforced in cinder/volume/api.py:create_snapshot(), which isn't in the code path of cgsnapshot_create.  This must be fixed.

Also, cgsnapshot_create() should be an atomic operation meaning we shouldn't allow 5 vols in total 6 vols of a CG have snapshot created, the rest was blocked by quota.

So I think the workflow should be: reserve snapshot quota for all vols in CG in cinder/consistencygroup/api.py:create_cgsnapshot(), commit the quota when operation succeeded.  Delete should free snapshot quota as well."}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-07-24 03:45:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

Hi Winston,

I made changes to snapshot quota as you suggested.

In _create_cgsnapshot() in cinder/consistencygroup/api.py, line 388, volume_api.create_snapshots_in_db() is called.

create_snapshots_in_db() is defined in cinder/volume/api.py, line 561.

It reserves snapshot quota for all volumes in CG, creates db entries, commits the quota at the end if successful; otherwise it rolls back the reservations.

Quota will be freed when cgsnapshot is deleted.  This is handled in cinder/volume/manager:delete_cgsnapshot().  When a single snapshot is deleted, quota is freed in cinder/volume/manager:delete_snapshot().

Please take a look.  Thanks!'}, {'account_id': 6094, 'date': '2014-07-28 07:59:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Sorry if I missed some discussion here. Want to raise some design related issues here.

Is consistency group for now only related to 1 backend at a time? It cannot spawn multiple backends?

How are 4 new methods useful in the volume driver?

Consistency groups as a principle are used to provide consistent state management across related/unrelated entities. For this use case of consistent snapshots why can we not handle it as follows:

1. when a cgsnapshot is requested and request comes to volume api.
2. volume api checks for all volumes associated with cg and gets the host for each.
3. It coordinates and issues snapshot requests for all volumes on the hosts.
4. Finally updates the cg state as completed, partial, or failed.

The current design will go on adding new methods in the driver for new uses of consistency groups.'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-07-29 00:19:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 18:

(4 comments)

Thanks Navneet for your review!

Yes, the assumption is that volumes in the same consistency group belong to the same backend.  See more details in the cinder spec:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/96665/8/specs/juno/consistency-groups.rst

In the current implementation of consistencygroup for LVM, I can't do quiesce yet.  So it may not appear to you that it should be a driver function. Once the quiesce feature becomes reliable in the next phase, I'll do quiesce first, take all snapshots in the driver, and then un-quiesce.  The quiesce can't be initiated by the volume API because the API works asynchronously.  After quiesce, we'll have to wait until all snapshots are taken before un-quiesce.  This needs to be handled by a volume manager which calls the driver.

For arrays that support consistency group technology at the storage level, in order to take a snapshot of a consistency group, the driver will have to know what volumes are involved and perform the action together.  Let's say there are 5 volumes in a consistency group.  The array will do a storage level quiesce first, take snapshots of all 5 volumes, and then un-quiesce at the end.

Please let me know if I have addressed your concerns.  Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 6094, 'date': '2014-07-29 15:08:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18:

Thanks Xing for the explanation. If the initial version is to have consistency group only related to one vendor at a time then the driver methods may be required. However I am still not purely convinced if the initial implementation should start by providing cg per backend. In the cinder meetings we decided that we should start simple on the impl and then extend it further. My understanding about starting simple was:

1. We will construct a common base framework for cgs. Which would make more sense if cg was a general impl for all backends. So it will not be restricted to one cg per backend which is the case now. This may be done in api or introducing a cgmanager at some layer.

2. In future we will extend this common framework for vendors which have cg capability so they can do cg management and cg initiated snapshot/storage entity management themselves.

The current initial design seems to be favoring the vendors which have the capability and not providing a common capability for all, in my view its contradictory to the design concept of cinder. 

Also on the question of lvm quiece operations, my question is does lvm not support snapshot operations currently? How do they snapshot the volumes now, can that same technique be not applied in case of cg?'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-07-29 19:12:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 18:

Hi Navneet,

Consistency group is an advanced feature, just like remote replication is an advanced feature.  If we implement it as a common feature for all, we cannot guarantee that it will really work for every driver.  Driver maintainer who thinks their driver can support this feature can implement this and test this and make sure it really works.

LVM does support snapshot.  The only thing I'm planning to add is the quiesce call to freeze the filsystem I/O before taking the snapshot.  Creating snapshot itself is still the same as before.

Hope this addresses your concerns.  We can discuss more if you still have doubts.  Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-07-29 22:12:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 18:

Hi Navneet,

If we don't provide driver level implementation of CG, there's no way for some backends to support CG even if they have the capabilities.  I believe that is the case for NetApp arrays as well.  Based on the document I read, NetApp Data ONTAP has CG APIs that support crash-consistent snapshots of volumes in a CG.  It has APIs such as cg-start, cg-commit, and cg-delete.  The document I read may not be up to date, but I think the idea is still correct.  It is not possible for the array to manage the volumes in a CG as one logical entity if the array is not aware of the grouping at all.  If this is implemented only at a higher level (the manager level) without any driver functions, the driver can't pass this information to the array and therefore this feature won't be useful for many vendors.

Please re-evaluate and let me know your thoughts.  Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 8587, 'date': '2014-07-30 03:20:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18: Code-Review-1

'}, {'created': '2014-07-20 22:14:59.000000000', 'message': "Consistency Groups

This patch enables Consistency Groups support in Cinder.
It will be implemented for snapshots for CGs in phase 1.

Design
------------------------------------------------
The workflow is as follows:

1) Create a CG, specifying all volume types that can be supported by this
CG. The scheduler chooses a backend that supports all specified volume types.
The CG will be empty when it is first created.   Backend needs to report
consistencygroup_support = True.  Also volume type needs to have
{'capabilities:consistencygroup_support': '<is> True'} in extra_specs.
The scheduler will make sure the selected backend reports consistency group
support.

To find out what volume types support CG:
cinder extra-specs-list | grep consistencygroup_support

Create CG CLI:
cinder consistencygroup-create --volume-type type1,type2 mycg1

This will add a CG entry in the new consistencygroups table.

2) After the CG is created, create a new volume and add to the CG.
Repeat until all volumes are created for the CG.

Create volume CLI (with CG):
cinder create --volume-type type1 --consistencygroup-id <CG uuid> 10

This will add a consistencygroup_id foreign key in the new volume
entry in the db.

3) Create a snapshot of the CG (cgsnapshot).

Create cgsnapshot CLI:
cinder cgsnapshot-create <CG uuid>

This will add a cgsnapshot entry in the new cgsnapshots table, create
snapshot for each volume in the CG, and add a cgsnapshot_id foreign key
in each newly created snapshot entry in the db.

Limitation/Known Issue
------------------------------------------------
LVM doesn't have storage level CG technology.  The proposal is to
leverage the filesystem level quiesce feature to achieve consistency
for LVM.  This step will be added in the next phase when the QEMU guest
agent filesystem freeze feature becomes reliable.

CCLA SCHEDULE B SUBMISSION

Implements: blueprint consistency-groups

Change-Id: Ic105698aaad86ee30ef57ecf5107c224fdadf724

in each newly created snapshot entry in the db.

------------------------------------------------

commit_message:
Consistency Groups

This patch enables Consistency Groups support in Cinder.
It will be implemented for snapshots for CGs in phase 1.

Design
------------------------------------------------
The workflow is as follows:

1) Create a CG, specifying all volume types that can be supported by this
CG. The scheduler chooses a backend that supports all specified volume types.
The CG will be empty when it is first created.   Backend needs to report
consistencygroup_support = True.  Volume type can have the following in
extra specs: {'capabilities:consistencygroup_support': '<is> True'}.
If consistencygroup_support is not in volume type extra specs, it will be
added to filter_properties by the scheduler to make sure that the scheduler
will select the backend which reports consistency group support capability.

Create CG CLI:
cinder consisgroup-create --volume-type type1,type2 mycg1

This will add a CG entry in the new consistencygroups table.

2) After the CG is created, create a new volume and add to the CG.
Repeat until all volumes are created for the CG.

Create volume CLI (with CG):
cinder create --volume-type type1 --consisgroup-id <CG uuid> 10

This will add a consistencygroup_id foreign key in the new volume
entry in the db.

3) Create a snapshot of the CG (cgsnapshot).

Create cgsnapshot CLI:
cinder cgsnapshot-create <CG uuid>

This will add a cgsnapshot entry in the new cgsnapshots table, create
snapshot for each volume in the CG, and add a cgsnapshot_id foreign key
in each newly created snapshot entry in the db.

DocImpact
Implements: blueprint consistency-groups

Change-Id: Ic105698aaad86ee30ef57ecf5107c224fdadf724

commit_message:
Add Server software_config_transport POLL_TEMP_URL

POLL_TEMP_URL will create a swift object with a newly
created UUID as the object name, in a container that matches
physical_resource_name.

Two TempURLs are created to this object, one to GET object
contents, and another to PUT.

The GET TempURL is used for the os-collect-config configured
metadata_url. The PUT url is stored in resource data so that
it can be retrieved in EngineService when deployment data
needs to be pushed out.

The object name is also stored in resource data so that the
object can be deleted during handle_delete. The container
is also deleted if deleting the object results in an empty
container.

Partial-Blueprint: swift-deployment-transport
Change-Id: Id644882a110171c12db8c34cfde02afc3d1d8626

commit_message:
Allow method verb override in get_temp_url

This will allow TempURLs to be used for GET too.

Change-Id: I0eb896d1a5a9a6b54aaa95e7942cc0d48108ea63
Partial-Blueprint: swift-deployment-transport

(1 comment)

Responding to Q's on the original review:

> Re the logic, does libvirt not have its own validation? 
> Do you have an example of processing that libvirt does 
> that is susceptible to attack using this method?

Libvirt allows a large range of options to be specified in the URI, including parameters which specify the path to external commands to invoke to setup the connection. It is valid for Libvirt to allows these parameters, but OpenStack should not allow the user of the migration APIs to influence this - they must only be able to influence the hostname of the target. 


> BTW if this is a valid security issue, the process is to
> first create a bug tagging it as sensitive (private), at
> which point the nova security team will evaluate it. (This
> may have been done in this case but I don't know which is
> the correct bug).

The referenced bug was originally considered a security issue, but after investigation it was found not to be exploitable in Nova, since the hostname was always used to lookup an entry in the compute hosts table before getting to libvirt. This patch is adding an explicit defence line as a way reduce the chance of a future exploitable bug."}, {'account_id': 1812, 'date': '2014-08-27 10:44:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

Thanks for the details Daniel. The original review didn't reference the correct bug, so I was missing lots of context.

This all looks good now, thanks Karen."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-27 10:44:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
libvirt: add validation of migration hostname

The migration hostname is substituted into the libvirt migration
URI string. If the hostname contains special characters it might
be possible to construct a malicious migration URI causing libvirt
to execute arbitrary commands as root. Protect against such a risk
by validating the hostname characters.

Change-Id: Ia3c53df1a842b5ef88f1f7ed5a3f4121df698161
Closes-bug: #1276862

commit_message:
Add support for setting up Designate quotas

We want to be able to set quotas so we can create more resources with a minimum
of 1

Change-Id: Icd9108b30bf8760d472bc2b82e489170ff7a5c37

commit_message:
Fix FloatingIP.save() passing FixedIP object to sqlalchemy

This prevents the FloatingIP.save() method from passing the
calculated FixedIP object to the sqlalchemy floating_ip_update()
function, which would expect it to be an SA object. It also
aborts any attempt to save the object with a modified fixed_ip_id
linkage, as associate/disassociate should be used for that.

This also fixes a bug where FloatingIP expects the result of
floating_ip_update() to be a FloatingIp SA object.

Added missing import to allow tests to work in stable/icehouse.

Change-Id: I065caedf4d81c8583a3b390934a1d403cf2e87bd
Closes-bug: #1334164
(cherry picked from commit 48de2895b9a550a0944b31212349275605a4061d)

commit_message:
Require Class['mysql::server'], not Service['mysqld'] when creating DB.

When using version >= 2.2 of the MySQL module, setting up the database
for Trove depended on the MySQL service (Service['mysqld']). However,
if the service is not managed by Puppet (e.g. it is managed through
Pacemaker instead), this would cause catalog compilation to fail because
there is no Service['mysqld']. This is the case when the MySQL module is
called with service_manage => false. Requiring Class['mysql::server']
instead fixes this.

Change-Id: I455d8e11d5ec18661fd18e797df9e5c7b654700d
Closes-Bug: 1349316

commit_message:
Change v3 extended_status to v2.1

This patch changes v3 extended_status API to v2.1 and makes v2
unit tests share between v2 and v2.1.
Revert v3 changes back to v2.
os-extended-status:* -> OS-EXT-STS:*
The differences between v2 and v3 are descibed on the wiki page
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3.
Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Ieefca1d0e8da831830f43cc83eb50bc7e7f4a10c

Arista Layer 3 Sevice Plugin

This sevice plugin implements routing functions on Arista HW.

commit_message:
Remove oauth controller dependency on token_api

The oauth controllers now use a mixture of internal callbacks and
the token_provider_api.validate_token instead of directly calling
the token_api delete token methods.

Change-Id: I454a592747dc5a4438541a8cecbcd796dd8378ab
bp: non-persistent-tokens

commit_message:
fix StringIO errors in unit test

alarm tests are throwing StringIO failures as it's being closed to soon.
change the way we capture logging.

Change-Id: Ifd956b8fe144219d029f8afb369ec25d13177078
Closes-Bug: #1329692
(cherry picked from commit c0702b298a8614a713ca392d0fcdb9bdaae9faac)

Revert use of olsosphinx library

not be using the openstack brand, and oslosphinx extensions when
building documentation

(5 comments)'}, {'account_id': 11970, 'date': '2014-08-27 18:16:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

As i'm thinking through this, here are my thoughts:

Customer Submits CSR &/or Data --> Barbican validates data (correct format...) --> Symantec (or other plugin) receives data --> Symantec kicks back a message w/ an error (WHOIS, Yellowbook, bad address... whatever) --> Barbican flips from PENDING to ERROR --> Customer is notified.

In this case, creating a *new* order wouldn't make sense to me. Sure, in our internal manual process we get a few auto-cancelations because they timed out -- but that isn't always the case. Symantec (after 21 days) will send a message back stating they canceled the order and this would update the status from ERROR to DONE.

But if we are just going to tweak the field (or have the customer contact Symantec to do an update) there is no reason for the order to be set up again brand new.

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 9914, 'date': '2014-08-27 19:42:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm ok with being able to update the order after it has been set in the ERROR state,  We will after all, have the ability to modify an order (which I believe you are adding).

I just don't think the order should be left in the PENDING state,"}, {'account_id': 9914, 'date': '2014-08-28 01:45:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-28 05:31:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Fix config option names in ml2_conf_sriov.ini

Config option names in ml2_conf_sriov.ini file are
not in sync with definitions in source code.

Change-Id: Ic8f7b6b8e9acd022623daabd2b209b864caa0b06
Closes-Bug: #1357339

utils.py, views.py and backend.py where using .replace('v3', 'v2.0') and
.replace('v2.0', 'v3') methods on url strings.
This is BAD because if you have v3 in your url's domain it brakes it.

A new url_path_replace method now only performs the replaces in the url path
and leaves the domain unchanged.

commit_message:
Added url_path_replace and has_in_url_path methods

utils.py, views.py and backend.py were using .replace('v3', 'v2.0') and
.replace('v2.0', 'v3') methods on url strings.
This is BAD because if you have v3 in your url's domain it brakes it.

A new url_path_replace method now only performs the replaces in the url path
and leaves the domain unchanged.

Some checks where performed to test if a substring was in the url path but the
tests where performed on the whole url and could return a false positive if the
substring exists in the domain name or in the query string.
The new has_in_url_path method checks only if the substring is in the path of
the url.

Change-Id: I030d928d83e5c91cf26101221649a299d146747d
Closes-Bug: 1324948

commit_message:
Remove docs about deprecated pypi-mirror tool

The pypi-mirror tool is no longer supported by the infra team, or
reccomended for installs, and is known to have various bugs that will
not be fixed.

Remove mentions of it from the docs and point people at devpi-server
instead.

Change-Id: Ieedb8bf9bee2f5932edac6b9747e645d0f4eb08c

commit_message:
Change V3 access_ips extension into v2.1

This patch changes v3 access_ips API to v2.1 and makes v2
unit tests share between v2 and v2.1.
The differences between v2 and v3 are described on the wiki page
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3 .

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Id464cbe4a8b7a7749c4f14e4531e4494dd315857

commit_message:
scope warnings to only display if the services are enabled

On my devstack environments I'm now always getting the Q_AGENT
warnings even though I don't have neutron enabled. This is mostly
confusing.

For these juno warnings lets just make sure that the whole thing
only prints out in the case where we've actually got that service
enabled.

Change-Id: I7d1bb2e65594c8bee2f572ca58a1b666e5d6caed

commit_message:
Change v3 agents API to v2.1

This patch changes v3 agents API to v2.1 and makes v2 unit tests
share between v2 and v2.1.

The differences between v2 and v3 are described on the wiki page
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3 .

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I96dd9cd3672c6d584bd0019c385544c08f687e7f

commit_message:
VMware: Add in support for CPU shares in event of resource contention

The flavor extra specs for quotas has been extended to support
 quota:cpu_shares_level - the allocation level. This can be 'custom', 'high'
                          'normal' or 'low'.
 quota:cpu_shares_share - in the event that 'custom' is used, this is the
                          number of shares.

This enables the VMware driver to provide CPU shares.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Iba55f91a5374ec6a1412e726a7ae2fbf2641155b

commit_message:
VMware: add resource limits for CPU

The flavor extra specs for quotas has been extended to support
 quota:cpu_limit - upper bound of CPU allocation (MHz)
 quota:cpu_reservation -  guaranteed minimum CPU allocation (MHz)

This enables the VMware driver to provide enable CPU allocations
for the running instance.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I1bec4f009285f7991eaaa8155329366a4eba5e1f

commit_message:
Change v3 security_groups API to v2.1

This patch changes v3 security_groups API to v2.1 and makes v2 unit tests
share between v2 and v2.1.
This patch doesn't revert /os-security-groups, /os-security-group-rules
and /servers/server_id/os-security-groups because these features are
implemented in Networking API. On v2.1 API, we decide we don't need to
implement proxying features.

The differences between v2 and v3 are described on the wiki page
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3 .

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I5b84273a7bf5eebc4d15ed3e55d94753f7c46b3d

commit_message:
Port simple_tenant_usage into v2.1

The simple_tenant_usage extension is removed from v3 API. For now,
we need porting it back. And also try to share unittests between v2
and v2.1.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Ie0c36fcd37fb188c1f1b57f04733bfa267b65201

commit_message:
Fix unit tests with keystoneclient master

This patch in python-keystoneclient breaks unit tests in Ironic:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/113712/

If admin_user is not passed to keystoneclient, an exception is
raised.

This patch overrides config for admin_user in Ironic's unit tests
to get around this behavior.

Closes-Bug: 1362280
Change-Id: I3a21e7c1b3a87ebee5a0e81f805f50919ef6a6d5

commit_message:
Add networks property to OS::Trove::Instance

Trove client recently added possibility to provide NICS while creating
Trove instances, which is required in presence of multiple Neutron
networks. This patch adds such property to OS::Trove::Instance resource,
allowing usage of this new feature in Heat.

Closes-Bug: #1312474
Change-Id: Ie691702bb2e2537397ed7ae657eb8d088424d890

commit_message:
Fix l3 agent scheduling logic to avoid unwanted failures

In case router is being added to l3 agent which is already hosting
the router it is fine to let such a request to succeed.
This patch also adds a check for unnecessary scheduling that might happen
twice in described case and lead to unwanted messages in the logs.

Change-Id: Id104b36ba7e1e6f6a9378ee600c33e9962230521
Closes-Bug: #1358636

commit_message:
Always replace a failed resource on rollback

If a resource is in the DELETE_FAILED state after an update, then we need
to create a replacement for it when rolling back the update, since its
actual underlying status cannot be determined (it may still exist, or it
may actually be gone or unusable).

Change-Id: Ibd2beae673b28d957d71cc7ae25070639e36bd36

commit_message:
Fix hosts fake int-tests assertion

Reasons:
 - hosts tests are failing due to wrong assertion because nova fake
   implementation sets used RAM taken from flavor info and it causes assertion error when
   flavor RAM gets compared with itself. Assertion should be changed from:
       usedRAM < totalRAM to usedRAM <= totalRAM

Changes:
 - fixing assertion for hosts tests.

Change-Id: I6becb061910c7ccb827b83029f7dc5814e9e7486
Closes-Bug: #1362318

commit_message:
Changes memcached to listen on internal address

Limits memcached binding to internal address only and changes OpenStack
components to only connect to that port. Tested with non HA and HA deployments.

Change-Id: I0e8bca92a7d79a83bed489146a5821c719f8f1bf
Closes-Bug: 1355079

commit_message:
Move _is_mapping to more central location

The logic to identify volumes is currently a nested function
in _default_block_device_names, named _is_mapping. It should
be moved to a more general location so others could utilize it
and allow it to be properly unit tested. The following patch
moves _is_mapping to nova/virt/block_device.py and renames it
to is_block_device_mapping.

Change-Id: I560abc4b57ca5bd195282af7cd1ab9bbf7600b67
Closes-Bug: #1351810

commit_message:
Remove docutils pin

This was added to work around bug 1091333.  A new sphinx has been
released and so this is no longer necessary.

Change-Id: I9107884d964757a9154bdd1feb4ea6df4e9df43e

commit_message:
Unittests: Refactor Volume resources tests

Changes include:
- use native HOT template with native Cinder resources for Cinder
  resources tests
- split tests in two test cases, one for AWS, another for native
  resources
- added base test case with most common boilerplate mocking

Change-Id: I9633a4b4eb0dc2403053ad9da6f34801604dbdce

Pass properties to Resource._needs_update()

When we start obtaining old property values from the database instead of
the old template, we will want to compare them separately.

Change-Id: I0b6ca33a320aa74e77991e7d0a5f9291e61fc88c

commit_message:
handle repeating mysqld options containing equals

Let load_mysqld_options handle repeating options such as:
"--plugin-load=blackhole=ha_blackhole.so
--plugin-load=federated=ha_federated.so" without crashing by storing all
the mysql_options we get in a dictionary with lists as values.

Change-Id: I634532e13bab80d476e4a1e8558b23da33656f60
Closes-Bug: #1348652

I think the wording you submitted is an improvement, but I also want to make sure that we are providing better explanations of the concepts that might be unfamiliar to new OpenStack users. 

Here are some wording recommendations:


aggregates/workflows.py

-Create a host aggregate to organize instances -> Host aggregates divide an availability zone into logical units by grouping together hosts. Create a Host aggregate then select the hosts contained in it.


aggregates/_update.html

-Create a host aggregate to organize instances -> Host aggregates divide an availability zone into logical units by grouping together hosts. Edit the aggregate host to select hosts contained in it.

-Add hosts to this aggregate... -> Add hosts to this aggregate. Hosts can be in multiple aggregates.

-Add hosts to this aggregate or remove hosts from it. ? Add hosts to this aggregate or remove hosts from it. Hosts can be in multiple aggregates.

domains/workflows.py

-Create a domain to organize projects, groups, projects, groups and users. -> Domains provide separation between users and infrastructure used by different organizations.

-Edit the domain details.  -> Domains provide separation between users and infrastructure used by different organizations. Edit the domain details to change add or remove groups in the domain.


flavors/workflows.py

Create a flavor to organize instance resources -> Flavors define the sizes for RAM, disk, number of cores, and other resources and can be selected when users deploy instances. 

Edit the flavor details. -> Edit the flavor details. Flavors define the sizes for RAM, disk, number of cores, and other resources. Flavors are selected when users deploy instances.

Control access to this flavor by moving projects from the... -> Select the projects where the flavors will be used. If no projects are selected, then the flavor will be available in all projects.


groups/_create.html

Create a new group to organize users and roles. -> Groups are used to manage access and assign roles to multiple users at once. After creating the group, edit the group to add users.

Edit the group's details. -> Groups are used to manage access and assign roles to multiple users at once. Edit the group to add users.


projects/workflows.py

Set maximum quotas for the project. -> Edit quotas for the project to change limits set in the default quotas.


Create a project to organize users.  -> Projects are used to assign resources shared by multiple users. 

Edit the project details -> Projects are used to assign resources shared by multiple users. Edit the project to manage users or quotas.


users/_create.html

Create a new user and set related properties including the Primary Project and Role.


users/_update.html

Edit the user's details, including their default project. -> Edit the user details, including the Primary Project and Role.


security_groups/_create.html

Create a new security group  -> Security groups are sets of IP filter rules that are applied to the networking settings for the VM. Edit the security group to add and change the rules.


security_groups/_update.html

Modify name and description of a security group. -> Security groups are sets of IP filter rules that are applied to the networking settings for the VM. Edit the security group to add and change the rules."}, {'account_id': 9622, 'date': '2014-08-21 22:34:00.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-22 00:07:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

commit_message:
Improve help messages on modals

Some general guidelines:
1. Removed contractions
2. Changed "Info" to "Information"
3. Removed the "From here you can..." at the beginning of messages.
4. Explained concepts to users instead of just reiterating the modal
title. Thanks Jeff Calcaterra!

Co-Authored-By: Cindy Lu <clu@us.ibm.com>
Closes-Bug: #1329984

Change-Id: I35af81953cafcbafc28c31b3ce305e8c5e21fe84

commit_message:
Add subnets attribute to OS::Neutron::Port resource

Added subnets attribute to the port resource to fetch the subnet
attributes such as gateway_ip which are associated with the port.

Change-Id: Ia809c343d5b7d1488b505f9e9e20da02b36de07d
Closes-Bug: #1336656

commit_message:
AWS SecurityGroup use is_using_neutron()

Allow for better decision on what networking backend to use when working
with AWS::EC2::SecurityGroup.

Change-Id: I6c887e76d4852d298ae8537486665291739c1f99

commit_message:
Move from using zookeeper to track partition offsets to kafka

With kafka 0.8.1 it is now possible for non-java clients to track
offsets with kafka. Previously the code had built this using zookeeper.
This relies on kafka-python > 0.9.1

Change-Id: Ia42e713cc5d9ca61d8f8df2adc454f1e2579a229

commit_message:
add new section "Preparing for NSX integration"

- briefly describe installation steps
- describe configuration steps that are important:
  * user has to write down Transport zone UUID and Gateway Service UUID
  * user has to choose transport type for gateway node, he must use the
    same transport type on Settings tab
- provide URLs that describe detailed process of installation and
  configuration NSX cluster
- provide instructions how to host NSX specific packages on Fuel Master
  node
- limitation: only NSX 4.0 is supported
- limitation: only KVM or QEMU are supported as hypervisor options
- limitation: entities that were created in NSX cluster are not flushed
  on "Reset Environment" or "Delete Environment" actions ("Reset" and
  "Delete" buttons on the Actions tab)

Change-Id: Ia30204479ac5ef3210a008561d7a338a8bd314a5
Implements: blueprint update-release-notes-fuel-5.1

commit_message:
Add headers for ceilometer, heat - and shared ones

Add more headers, regenerate ceilometer and heat tables with them.
Create shared header file and remove duplicate entries.

Change-Id: Ia5bcda0d5daaed19636b426d6e25469f0d4bbcfa

commit_message:
Check if the alarm has time constraints field before displaying

Fixes the bug that broke the alarms CLI if the alarm didn't have
a time constraints field.

Reduces code duplication of alarm printing code, so now all the alarm
printing code is actually tested.

Renames some auxiliary methods for more clarity.

Change-Id: Ib691b4a5a6cf5ae133cd0a5576f90e4d0d189a92
Closes-bug: #1316390

commit_message:
Fix collection order issues and unit test failures

A randomized PYTHONHASHSEED caused the glance API to return certain data
in a nondeterministic order, breaking some tests. This patch sorts the
returned data before testing against a pre-sorted expected values.

Change-Id: Ie294b64738bd33b31aea915183c30b5b8db2eb65

commit_message:
Backport V3 hypervisor plugin unit tests to V2

This patch backport some of the V3 hypervisor plugin unit tests
to V2 unit tests.

Change-Id: Ieeadb66dcd142c1919912703b4e410cfa1aa15f2

commit_message:
Mark kvs backends as deprecated, for removal in Kilo.

Although kvs.Base was marked from removal in Juno, the backends
themselves were not explicitly marked. This patch does this,
as well as extendes kvs.Base also to Kilo so that they can all
be removed together.

Partially implements: bp deprecated-as-of-juno
Change-Id: Ia2e7c95074c4b6b9743c6086842105a5579fc0c9

commit_message:
Add language attribute to code samples

Create the literal_block nodes with a 'language' attribute to add syntax
highlighting in the generated documentation.

This change is not visible in the HTML output, but is used when the
generated XML is imported in the openstack-manuals hot-reference book
(WIP).

The 'hot' language is not currently supported in sphinx or in the
manuals, but it doesn't hurt to have it and it could be implemented
later.

Change-Id: Ie5d4ab31665da812ccd7ec1232d3858786170477
Implements: blueprint heat-templates
Closes-Bug: #1360559

commit_message:
XenAPI support: Changes for cpu_util

Implemented inspect_cpu_util() to inspect the CPU utilization (%)
for an instance.

Change-Id: I0cd1c926f074be632d9c5ce071dfd4d0d3ba78a7
Implements: blueprint xenapi-support

commit_message:
Raise NotImplementedError instead of NotImplemented

NotImplementedError is the name of the exception
(https://docs.python.org/2/library/exceptions.html).

NotImplemented is the name of a constant
(https://docs.python.org/2/library/constants.html).

It makes no sense to raise a constant. The exception should
be raised instead.

Change-Id: I4969e26eb7b46f008ea3c8bd0093490c425f7069
Closes-Bug: #1339855

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Use real exceptions for network create and destroy

In order to provide reasonable error messages to the user, we
need real exceptions instead of a bunch of random value Errors.

Partially-implements blueprint better-support-for-multiple-networks

Change-Id: Id725afbdde40cba879608d15de9aa2753a256d10

Here I wanted to explain the issue/problem:
Problem is: The terminate_instance returns the instanceset info with instance_ID, current_stat and previous_stat.
As of now, the current_stat and previous_stat as same, when the terminate_instance API. This patch fixes this issue with correct current_stat.

Regarding the any issue on  terminating the instance-if the termination is not successful, then appropriate error message displayed by the specific api as "compute_api.delete".

commit_message: Fix the current state name as 'shutting-down' Currently, the TerminateInstance returns the currentstate name as previous state name. Ideally the TerminateInstance return element's currentstate named as "shutting-down". Addressed the issue and below is the terminateinstance response with fix: == req-c15f5c7d-2551-4a08-b8b8-255462a09592 i-00000001 32 shutting-down 16 running == And also updated the testcases in nova/tests/api/ec2/test_cloud.py appropriately. Closes-bug: #1322025 Change-Id: I790e7d86ef8fd9f4fc1612bae2788e0ae7ef9719

commit_message:
Load trove API extensions using stevedore

The current trove impl loads trove API extensions by searching on a
single file path which is exposed as a conf property. This results in a
less than optimal approach from a consumer extension POV. This change
replaces the single extension path approach with dyanmic loading  using
stevedore. Consumers can now bind into the API extensions using the
'trove.api.extensions' entry point; a standard means to define extension
points. Moreover this change refactors to the
trove.openstack.common.extensions logic into trove.common.extensions.

In addition this change includes base unit tests to ensure the
existing trove proper extension points are loaded and that some basic
checks are in place W/R/T validating trove extension points.

Change-Id: Id3e712b536aef3bc9c9d1603367cdc0d4816b970
Implements: blueprint dynamic-extension-loading

commit_message:
Allow use custom nameserver when setting up neutron subnet

By default nameserver in neutron subnet points to neutron server.
It's useful to allow users override the default DNS server if they
want to use their own.

Change-Id: Ia5b52d19d83f1dc894a808517ee1a742631aec99

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-04-10 18:36:57.000000000', 'message': 'Keep status_changed_at up-to-date with status changes.

In particular during container recreation and replication.

When a container-server receives a PUT for a deleted database an extra
UPDATE is issued against the container_stat table to notate the
x-timestamp of the request.

During replication if merge_timestamps causes a container's status to
change (from DELETED to ACTIVE or vice-versa) the status_changed_at
filed is set to the current time.

Accurate reporting of status_changed_at is useful for container
replication forensics and allows resolution of "set on create"
attributes like the upcoming storage_policy_index.

Change-Id: Ia4020391ba8a4f83d9901cab8c51ade6a92153ee
'}]
commit_message:
Keep status_changed_at up-to-date with status changes.

In particular during container recreation and replication.

When a container-server receives a PUT for a deleted database an extra
UPDATE is issued against the container_stat table to notate the
x-timestamp of the request.

During replication if merge_timestamps causes a container's status to
change (from DELETED to ACTIVE or vice-versa) the status_changed_at
filed is set to the current time.

Accurate reporting of status_changed_at is useful for container
replication forensics and allows resolution of "set on create"
attributes like the upcoming storage_policy_index.

Change-Id: Ia4020391ba8a4f83d9901cab8c51ade6a92153ee

In create() method of server, nova API parses extension parameters
from each extension's server_create() method by the following call:

   self.create_extension_manager.map(self._create_extension_point,
                                     server_dict, create_kwargs)

block_device_mapping value is parsed from 'os-block-device-mapping:
block_device_mapping' in os-block-device-mapping extension, and
min_count value is done from 'os-multiple-create:min_count'.
This patch fixes some wrong extension parameters in unit tests.

These bugs were found through jsonschema validation framework
development, because the framework doesn't allow undefined
parameters based on each schema.

commit_message:
Fix extension parameters in test_multiple_create

In create() method of server, nova API parses extension parameters
from each extension's server_create() method by the following call:

   self.create_extension_manager.map(self._create_extension_point,
                                     server_dict, create_kwargs)

block_device_mapping value is parsed from 'os-block-device-mapping:
block_device_mapping' in os-block-device-mapping extension, and
min_count value is done from 'os-multiple-create:min_count'.
This patch fixes some wrong extension parameters in unit tests.

os-block-device-mapping extension calls BlockDeviceDict.from_api()
method for getting bdm_type and uuid from "source_type" and "uuid",
but current these parameters also are wrong.
This patch fixes test block_device_mapping values also.

These bugs were found through jsonschema validation framework
development, because the framework doesn't allow undefined
parameters based on each schema.

Change-Id: I0d5899c84c7a7f2938a553d7ce845f855f1dfd7a

commit_message:
VMware: add adapter type constants

Commit 6a55d4281dbdd5462eafa08321207e7f71d5ebb0 introduced
default constants. This patch creates constants for different
adapter types used.

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I96481b86e8c90f754da05cfbfbd9cb89a7450d98

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Some tests used incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected).

The correct order expected by testtools is...

    def assertEqual(self, expected, observed, message=''):
        """Assert that 'expected' is equal to 'observed'.

        :param expected: The expected value.
        :param observed: The observed value.
        :param message: An optional message to include in the error.
        """

The string length of the sum of the results of repr(expected) and
repr(observed) is greater than 70, then, MismatchError message is
changed, as below.

  Ex.:
        raise mismatch_error
    MismatchError: !=:
    reference = '_123456789_123456789_bar'
    actual    = '_123456789_123456789_123456789_123456789_123456789'

Change-Id: Id02ddfb2ca03df7f432cff67a7bed182cccc4924
Closes-Bug: #1259292

commit_message:
Add the configuration of worker process to serve the public/admin WSGI application

Now in the cookbook-openstack-identity cookbook, there are no default properties to
configure the number of worker process to serve the public or admin to serve
the WSGI application.

In the complex environment with multi nodes, the customer needs to configure more
public/admin worker processes during deploying with openstack identity cookbook.

Change-Id: I9d9f4d4c782200972034992dd83c5648a952eb84
Closes-Bug: 1361965

commit_message:
Add api extension for new network fields.

This uses the existing api extension to implement the actual control
of the fields, but the check is based on a new dummy extension
called os-extended-networks.

Api sample tests added for new extension.

DocImpact: Adds an extension that enables extra fields for network
create. The new fields are:
  mtu: int (default flag) if set, nova sets the mtu on bridge. This
       allows network_device_mtu flag to be set per network.
  dhcp_server: ip (default == gateway) if different from gateway, sets
                nova to assume gateway is external.
  enable_dhcp: bool (default true) false will disable dhcp on network.
  share_address: bool (default flag) if specifed, network will have
                 the same dhcp ip on every host. This allows
                 share_dhcp_address flag to be set per network.
  allowed_start: ip if specified, reserves all ips before allowed_start.
  allowed_end: ip if specified, reserves all ips after allowed_end.

Partially-implements blueprint better-support-for-multiple-networks

Change-Id: I577fe5f6560be50106f345a42a826e97d5e7d64c

commit_message:
Fix Neutron DB migration scripts execution logic

The migration scripts should be triggered by neutron-server package
installation, because it's required during upgrade.
Currently neutron-server is installed as a dependency for other packages, so
more strict packages ordering is required.

Change-Id: I5d10ff9df6a37ad807d0d0214f3a6113bd58c08c
Closes-bug: #1361541

commit_message:
Centralize handling of /lost+found

Just remove globally /lost+found after the root and install phases, so
distribution elements don't need to do that by themselves.

Change-Id: Ic783e613bd8794aefd3f40c9a7c308d14cd04b8d

commit_message:
How to install Fuel on vSphere

ref-arch -- add 7000-vcenter- -- add info about
how Fuel is run under vSphere

planning-guide -- add 7300-fuel-on-vsphere-prepare
which needs some information about how to plan for this

user-guide -- add 7350-fuel-on-vsphere.rst with instructions
for preparing the vCenter for the Fuel installation
and installing Fuel on vSphere

Change-Id: Ib6cc7f55e716459ce41a7826074aa25406fd64e2

commit_message:
Initial connect orders resource to certificate processing

Connects the new orders type/meta API to the issue_certificate_request()
method of certificate worker tasking logic. The order plugin metadata is not
provided with this CR. Saving a certificate into a Container is also not
provided with this CR. This CR does address issues with the orders resource
processing.

Change-Id: Id5c6c06ecccd3d4d7eb27d974156dba06bd8fe6f
Implements: blueprint add-ssl-ca-support

commit_message:
Splits generic validation tests from model tests

There is no reason to run the generic tests for every model we are
testing. Also in doing the split I noticed that there were a couple of
places using the wrong schema.

Change-Id: I4c117fcce867ba7ccd51099614862c4827d8843b

commit_message:
Update API document with BootDevice

This patch adds description about above BootDevice Web APIs.
* GET v1/nodes/(node_uuid)/management/boot_device
* GET v1/nodes/(node_uuid)/management/boot_device/supported
* PUT v1/nodes/(node_uuid)/management/boot_device

Change-Id: I2826e59332102b258b72e9850baa1a6b0d189f79

commit_message:
libvirt: Uses correct imagebackend for configdrive

When the configdrive file is created it must be moved to the
configured imagebackend, not always the raw one.

Otherwise nova can't boot an instance with a configdrive attached
when the rbd backend is configured.

Related to bug #1246201
Closes-bug: #1361840

Change-Id: I59578d9b87a36ff4417a30ff14c5774c54698cf3

commit_message:
Make RHSM registration set -u safe

There are a bunch of optional env vars references in the rhsm
registration script, but they weren't wrapped to be set -u safe so
they cause build failures if any aren't set.

Change-Id: I18326b618f0920efa4dbd805611c6ee66d33ebb0

commit_message:
Remove duplicated negative factors in keypair test

In test_keypair_create_fail_policy, there are two negative factors.
One is a policy violation, and another is a bad request body.
The purpose of the test is checking the policy violation, so a bad
request body is not right for this test.
This patch removes a bad request body from the test.

Change-Id: Ia165e08410b0576950efe83e5ab6a92c9c7f6a50

    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Change wget to curl for using both of them is redundant

heat-cfntools depends on wget and curl. It's redundant.
Since the curl is widely used, replace wget command to curl.

Change-Id: I691bdc046bd72a44c11f25e359c5036ae1a9e86b
Closes-Bug: 1359430

commit_message:
Preserve exception text during schedule retries

This fix preserves the exception text (as intended) when the number
of scheduling retries exceeds the maximum attempts.  We don't pop
the exception message anymore in _log_compute_error so that the
final "max attempts" error message has an opportunity to dump it
as well.

This defect caused the exception text (from the compute process) to
ALWAYS be None, thus making it difficult to triage compute errors.

Change-Id: I5c7cac1d79dc583cca523270bb0a96d3353ca1f6
Closes-Bug: #1361097

commit_message:
Revert "Add workaround for reloading haproxy on Fedora"

The upstream fix to the haproxy package has been released,
so this should no longer be necessary.

This reverts commit e3d26159bd1746fa8d10f77cbab798735da8d333.

Change-Id: Ic62222731b34897b1b8dc2bc88049655585b04d9

commit_message:
default to MULTI_HOST

Given that we want multi host environments to be a supported thing
we should just default to multi host in the base case for devstack,
as it's one less knob to turn.

Change-Id: I41e6055c9bf2f56145308cb8c6317db85e1a8489

commit_message:
Introducing 'workflow' as an individual entity

* Added Workflow DB model
* Removed 'workbook_name' parameter from Engine.start_workflow signature
* Fixed unit tests
* Fixed module trusts to create individual workbook entities when
 on workbook definition update
* Fixed API tests
* Switched v1 controllers to explicitly use DB API v1

Change-Id: I6a096e1c5d8082d3d1cdd47b575b85b28224d2a6

commit_message:
Renaming 'linear' workflow to 'direct'

* Linear workflow was not an accurate term for this workflow type
  and it will conflict with truly linear workflow that will appear
  later.

Change-Id: Ia9035d419bc720ce8397cf6f1493a968be948eeb
