(3 comments)

I agree with this patch in principal.
However, this will break secgroup.cross_tenant scenario, despite the fix you are doing, because the whole test is being done with incoming and outgoing ping, so allowing ping in the beginning of the test will defeat the test purpose.

I can think of 2 possible changes to the scenario that would solve this:
1. On "access_point" secgroup, allowing only ping from the specific ip of the machine running tempest. seems a little complicated, but will allow you to keep the test as is, and allow only this specific check.
2. Change the testing method, so instead of "ping" we test connectivity using "traceroute" via specific tcp/udp ports

Each change could be done as part of your patch, or as a different patch that should be pushed prior to this one.

If you want to handle this in a different patch, please let me know, and I will gladly do this myself.'}, {'account_id': 8576, 'date': '2014-07-30 12:45:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

Also:
The ping check will be called before any new command execution. I am concerned that this will put unnecessary strain on the VMs, network, etc..

I suggest caching the ping test so it's done only once per combo of (test_method, server). Once you've verified connectivity to the vm, you can move on with regular work.

Another approach is to attach the ping test to the auth test done on creation of new ssh_client instance"}, {'account_id': 12444, 'date': '2014-07-30 12:59:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)

I think that while pinging the destination host prior to starting a ssh connection is justified seeing as how confusing the exception reporting is, but changing a code that is *pure* ssh to also implicitly ping is not optimal.

I would suggest either making the ping an explicit feature (user might have, for example, disabled ICMP intentionally), or checking for connectivity some other way (traceroute?).'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2014-08-04 05:25:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

(5 comments)

My concern with the solution for the secgroup test is that it adds complexity to it.
It works in theory and as long as everything is fine, it won't damage anything.

However, we've seen bugs that were masked by creating and then deleting a rule, and I fear the new test flow would mask similar bugs.

commit_message:
ping before we ssh

For a sanity check, we should actually figure out if we can get
to the host at all before we ssh to it. This hopefully gives us
information about the state of the world before we blame it
entirely on ssh.

To enable this new check the neutron scenario tests in:
test_security_groups_basic_ops had to be modified to add a sec group
rule to allow icmp traffic. Otherwise the tests would fail when they
attempt to ssh into guests, because the ping sanity check added would
fail before ssh is ever used.

Related-Bug: #1298472
Co-Authored-By: Matthew Treinish <mtreinish@kortar.org>
Change-Id: I9e7f9a76ac4c9edadce6c7ba11a6aaead6e4bbb7

commit_message:
remove H305 because it's python version specific

If you make the code pass when running it under python2 it will
fail under python3 because of builtins that migrated it. As the
python stdlib is not fixed, but grows over time, this is actually
a counter productive test as we try to get towards python3, and
python versions that change over time.

Change-Id: I7e4d83d9663d8e59cce3d3254e37672ef4222199

commit_message:
disable apparmor

apparmor error messages seem to be showing up in libvirt logs
regarding snapshots. It is possibly related to our snapshot issues.

We already disable selinux, disabling apparmor should be par for
the course.

Change-Id: I283d50766e3fa9db94484789037b3bbf7604902e

commit_message:
Add support for interacting with swift

This commit introduces support for interacting with
swift for creating and deleting swift objects. This
will be initially used by ilo driver for hosting
temporary floppy images.

Change-Id: I9a3962820b7e18fb1014be1e43cb107facfede9f
Implements: blueprint ironic-ilo-virtualmedia-driver

commit_message:
Support for Python 3

Fix up various things to support Python 3. This also included removing
the pretty lines in README.rst, because tox with Python 3 just could
not cope.

Change-Id: I8e8a40ebc54ab781ccf0961a88fd1f8526aaeba0

Moving Fuel UI is available on: http://$(IP):8000 to two lines breaks the sed script in bootstrap_admin_node.sh. Move it back to 1 line and I will +1'}, {'account_id': 5319, 'date': '2014-08-13 14:23:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Matthew: Instead of moving it to two lines I changed the scripts: bootstrap_admin_node.sh and bootstrap_admin_node.docker.sh as you can see there is duplicate code, it changes /etc/issue which is already being changed in ks.template. Hence I have removed the duplicate code which was causing a bug that the previous no longer used sed line appeared two times /etc/rc.local
If you deploy the latest master branch you will notice the sed line appearing two times in /etc/rc.local

I will also do some more testing and reading of code to see the process of startup and deployment of admin node.

Thanks for pointing out the conflict with bootstrap_admin_node scripts that would have resulted in another bug. This is my first Fuel patch, so review with care :)'}, {'account_id': 5319, 'date': '2014-08-13 14:27:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-13 14:27:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

[{'created': '2014-08-12 18:07:00.000000000', 'message': 'WIP: Add improved SSH/Fuel web instructions

- List all the IP address on which Fuel UI is
  accessible instead of only eth0.
- Also added default username and password
  for Fuel UI.

Change-Id: Ib0605c298c6ef26e8cdceb07171b76cee96ae3f8
'}, {'created': '2014-08-12 18:31:35.000000000', 'message': 'WIP: Add improved SSH/Fuel web instructions

- List all the IP address on which Fuel UI is
  accessible instead of only eth0.
- Also added default username and password
  for Fuel UI, these are retrieved by
  directly reading from /etc/fuel/astute.yaml

Note: Reading directly from /etc/fuel/astute.yaml
may easy be prone to errors. Instead we can also
just hardcode the default, not sure which one is
better.

Closes-Bug: #1351937

Change-Id: Ib0605c298c6ef26e8cdceb07171b76cee96ae3f8

commit_message:
Add improved SSH/Fuel web instructions

- List all the IP address on which Fuel UI is
  accessible instead of only eth0.
- Also added default username and password
  for Fuel UI, hardcoded as admin/admin
- Removes duplicate code from
  bootstrap_admin_node scripts which was
  previously causing the sed line to
  appear twice in /etc/rc.local

Closes-Bug: #1351937

Change-Id: Ib0605c298c6ef26e8cdceb07171b76cee96ae3f8

commit_message:
Use --tmpdir with mktemp

Pass --tmpdir to mktemp so the new temporary directory is placed
within $TMPDIR, or falling back to /tmp. This way dib-run-parts can
use whatever the temporary directory is, instead of using an hardcoded
/tmp.

Change-Id: I6b55e3c6c1fe22108ea555d3766e0323695bd96d

commit_message:
Install fuelclient before containers on Fuel Master

Nailgun container needs /etc/fuel/client
configured because it mounts this path
read-only and errors during its puppet run.

Change-Id: I21d0d62d03821d1ccaf4b4bfabd2df8188120287
Closes-Bug: #1362614

commit_message:
Fix supervisord start with stale pidfile

supervisord has a stale pidfile sometimes
during Fuel container upgrades.
Also corrected whitespace issues.

Reduced wait time for processes to 5s so that
init script doesn't exceed its max timeout.

Change-Id: I6e5511f5fcce0205283594a290e72084b20e6aa7
Closes-Bug: #1361756

commit_message:
Allow table actions to be displayed in a menu

This adds the ability for table actions to be placed into an
actions menu above the table in addition to the current
button only format. This ability is not implemented in any
existing horizon table but is mainly meant for those who
build on horizon with tables that might have many actions.

To use a table actions menu, add a list of table action
classes to the table Meta class using the table_actions_menu
attribute. For example, to display the Soft Reboot and
Terminate actions in a menu on the project instances table
add this attribute to the project instances table Meta class:

    table_actions_menu = (SoftRebootInstance, TerminateInstance,)

Implements: blueprint table-action-menus
Change-Id: I02cd52f06be3fa11dd5fe0b45c8cc1e3bff5efdb

commit_message:
Fixes terminate_connection live migration issue

Reverts the changes to cinder/volume/manager.py added in
commit b868ae707f9ecbe254101e21d9d7ffa0b05b17d1 as calling
remove_export in terminate_connection causes Nova live
migration to fail when volumes are attached.

Change-Id: I38f3db336db22bb096a8855bcbbfeba16e517b80
Closes-Bug: #1361738

commit_message:
Fix concurrent policy issue in unittest

After merge of following commit: 4f17b8d837ebad4ef2e8ae5fe95ea968c7b8b587
appears unstable error when we get denial from policy check.
'Fix' mocks policy.check_policy method and tests that it was called.
We do not test policy actions in related unittest suite located in
'manila.tests.api.v1.test_share_networks' module, and should not.

Change-Id: I8885fa622e603c2e1882709d427e2fd1b532197c
Closes-Bug: #1362468

commit_message:
Fix flavor object can't delete extra_spec when deleted by del statement

The extra_spec can't be deleted by both v2 and v3 API. This is due to
when delete extra_spec's item by del statement, it won't trigger the
property setter, then flavor object won't know the extra_spec is changed.
This patch change flavor's save function to compare orignal extra_spec and
current extra_spec for getting it changed or not.

Change-Id: I82d21dbd4f8a9261c9263e3ccddead0144a758e5
Closes-Bug: #1362471

commit_message:
Repeat add-tenant and remove-tenant option in cli

For cisco-network-profile-create and cisco-network-profile-update cli,
add repeatable add-tenant and remove-tenant options so that user can
add and remove multiple tenants in a single cli request.

This fix includes changes in neutron, python-neutronclient and horizon.
All the changes should be merged at the same time

Implements: blueprint cisco-network-profile-multi-tenants-support
Change-Id: Ia902426b10d22a757ebbf62249dc28e9909dbff0

commit_message:
Add libxmlsec1 as external package dependency on OS X

This is required to use pysaml2.

There are several packages related to libxmlsec1 on Debian and Fedora,
and I'm not sure which is/are required without testing, so this patch is
limited to documenting the change required for OS X.

Implements bp keystone-to-keystone-federation

Change-Id: I61586a0b6d9411136f7e2d5a3f991bee4617f355

commit_message:
Fix the Neutron DB creation during deployment

Neutron database should be created by the Neutron db migration scripts,
but they are ignored during deployment of HA clusters. The problem is
the migration scripts depends on neutron-server package installation,
but it's installed as a dependency for the OVS server package, so no
necessary event was produced by Puppet. Now it's installed separately.

Closes-bug: #1361541

commit_message:
Use monasca everywhere

Rename all uses of mon-persister to monasca-persister. For example,
the service is now called monasca-persister not mon-persister

Rename all packages from com.hpcloud.mon.persister to monasca.persister

Change-Id: Ic131b0eb0ac30e9ae91ca1f2f9df88fc9f837c98

commit_message:
Check vlan parameter is valid

Now, we can create network with invalid vlan with nova-network.
Check if vlan parameter is greater than 4094 or less than 1.

Change-Id: I27a74fb76ba575f43fee669c0c495e0ef96d4b18
Closes-Bug: #1334563

commit_message:
Fix failed to delete the EIP resource

When AWS::EC2::EIP is failed to associate with
the server, it can't be delete. So we attempt
to disassociate and to catch the exception, and to
check if not associate we just ignore it while deletion.

Change-Id: I6a34398f27d6b21de9209de70bf8cc3c77d27149
Closes-Bug: #1334497

commit_message:
Update stack.load_all adding show_nested

Add a show_nested argument, defaulted to false, which will
show nested stacks, not just top-level ones.  Due to an
unfortunate collision in the way backup and nested stacks
are currently stored (both are identifiable by having an
owner_id), we have to filter the backup stack by name, if
it exists.  In a future patch this can be cleaned up by
modifying the DB schema to store data to more explicitly
specify backup stacks.

blueprint: list-nested
Change-Id: I1b2e44380cf2f9162dbc4d9bc300e15c325f0eca

commit_message:
Adds console script entry point

A Swift client executable needs to be provided on Windows since Python scripts
cannot be executed directly.

This approach is also consistent with other OpenStack Python clients (e.g.
Nova, Neutron, Cinder, etc.).

Change-Id: I7f03b7c305dceed4fa6f4fe1c1281659820606e4
Closes-Bug: #1359360

commit_message:
handle_signal to handle translated error msgs

Heat software config deployments, when they fail, in some
circumstances pass translateable Messages as their error output.

Patch converts messages to unicode rather than str.

Change-Id: Idd325c80b68a69d11cea306bd6980518f0948196
Closes-Bug: #1332355

commit_message:
Improve errors in Volume tasks

Produce more meaningful errors and warnings
when attachment/detachment/extension of the volume fails
due to wrong final volume status.

Change-Id: Icc04ecff9cc3a53585926d408f1f986212ff09b1

commit_message:
Add more info to ResourceUnknownStatus

Added an optional field 'result' to ResourceUnknownStatus exception
message describing the problem happend due to the said status
(defaults to 'Resource failed'). Also modified tests accordingly.

Change-Id: Id299aec598ea44cdb7d9fca5f8f580a177fef059

[{'created': '2014-01-08 10:51:12.000000000', 'message': 'Filters: Adds ability to configure disk_allocation_ratio from aggregates

Is now possible to use the filter AggregateDiskFilter and
define an aggregate with a metadata "disk_allocation_ratio" to
configure the ratio used for disk allocation oversubscribed.

  + Creates new filter AggregateDiskFilter
  + Adds a base class for DiskFilter
  + Updates devrefs for: DiskFilter and AggregateDiskFilter
  + Adds unit tests for AggregateDiskFilter

Note:
  This upgrade was largely inspired from AggregateRamFilter
  and AggregateCoreFilter.

DocImpact

filter: add per-aggregate filter to configure disk_allocation_ratio

Adds a filter AggregateDiskFilter which provides the ability to
read from aggregates metadata the "disk_allocation_ratio".

commit_message:
Configure haproxy keystone backend before keystone service

Configure haproxy keystone backend before keystone service
starts. This will fix ordering problem when we have keystone
resources created before keystone is available. Service
is already started before resources creation, so that
puppet provider will receive a couple of 503|504 HTTP
errors in the worst case and handle them.

Closes-bug: #1357386

Change-Id: I906fb01f678b0407e421a5db7f617901fed80f79

commit_message:
Use the template module to access the Template class

i.e. stop using parser.Template
this imports the template module as "templatem" to avoid
namespace clashes with the many local variables called "template".

Change-Id: I97cc893f630e46589ee71fc73c6bbbcaa86b3a62

commit_message:
Allow for setting ViP ID

Allows the user to specify the id of an existing
virtual ip rather than create a new one. This
allows devices listening on different ports using
the same ip addresses.

Change-Id: Ieba48abc0470cc5b596245efa51e9919ef37e0ca

commit_message:
Split scaling policy into separate files

A further step to split the AWS and the OS version of auto-scaling group
related classes.  This patch splits the scaling policy and launch
configuration into separate files.

This patch is not breaking any existing test cases. But more test cases
will be needed for the OS version scaling policy.

Implements: partial-blueprint reorg-asg-code
Change-Id: I0f888496d92b0efb5d63b567864488ff8a45e4ac

commit_message:
Cut down on warning logs

- don't log on ignore_not_found()
- drop some logs from warn to info
- remove the "no resources in template" log
- remove the "Duplicating event" log

Change-Id: Ie4d68b43607336c8c054a32126d6a05ba4e5e15c
Closes-bug: #1346755

commit_message:
Standardize AccessInfo token setting

When settings tokens via the factory v2 and v3 work completely
differently. This is somewhat expected due to tokens working differently
but it makes it hard to work with.

For example, if i have a v3 token but not the requests.Response that
created it there is no way for me to set the token data on the
AccessInfo object via factory.

Also in the case of V2 CMS tokens the value at ['token']['id'] is a fake
so that the signing process will work.

Allow overriding the token value from the factory and force setting the
token id on the AccessInfo in a standard way.

Change-Id: I856096dc5fae2ab0d1bedbac3294dc4976c3f3ad

commit_message:
Allow to decide between Nova-network and Neutron

Adds a heat.conf option to set the OpenStack component responsible for
networking, and makes heat-engine auto-discover the networking service
on start up if such option is not set.
Also adds a convenience method to Resource class to let resources decide
what networking service to use.

Implements blueprint discover-networking-service

Change-Id: If7121089068cc2d2774bedb73e4e252b520eb5b3

commit_message:
tests for Keystone endpoint V2 API

This patch adds the JSON/XML clients and tests for following
Keystone endpoint V2 APIs :
1. endpoint-create
2. endpoint-delete
3. endpoint-list

Change-Id: Ie563fd08e2581f3220beedd8fe7e3426b3dc5bc7

commit_message:
Remove assignment_api dependency on token_api

The assignment_api now uses the callback system to avoid needing
to directly call token_api for invalidating the tokens in the
token persistence system.

This change is in support of non-persistent tokens which has a
dependency on unifying interactions with the token persistence
system.

Change-Id: I66af0a7281cf9a4d451f0f6d86da8182e2cc0e60
bp: non-persistent-tokens

commit_message:
Port os-server-groups extension to work in v2.1/v3 framework

Ports v2 os-server-groups extension and adapts it to the v2.1/v3 API
framework. API behaviour is identical with the exception
that there is no support for XML. Also

- unittest code modified to share testing with both v2/v2.1
- Adds expected error decorators for API methods
- Adds api sample tests

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I52e49e6e85a7516e3b184601374e5c987f60a9a0

commit_message:
boolean parameter type is not recognized in the API

The boolean type that was added to Heat templates is not recognized
in the API layer. Because of this, the API passes the schema type
(which is lowercase 'boolean') directly to the client, while all
other recognized types are passed with camel case.

Change-Id: I0d31401456c0f5cd0bb81e29323e40b4de66f331
Closes-Bug: 1361448

commit_message:
Upgrades, run iptables cleaning only for required containers

I doesn't make sence to run iptables
cleaning, for containers, which
doesn't have port bindings, e.g.
volume containers.

Change-Id: I7c313e5bb2806cbf4beb067ace6c4dc614a73281
Closes-bug: #1362544

the repository.

commit_message:
Add user_domain_name in the user object

user_domain_name is exposed by keystoneclient, adding
this information for horizon as well.

Change-Id: Ic09b892bcb7669ed19a353e535d1aea43bbe92b7
Closes-Bug: #1360521

commit_message:
Add numa_topology column to the compute_node table

This patch adds the migration to add the numa_topology column to the
compute_node table. It also adds the field to the ORM model and the
Nova object class.

Change-Id: I4ca994662ed700a907f78aa04016b626fc351b25
Blueprint: virt-driver-numa-placement

commit_message:
Add a Set and SetOfIntegers object fields

Object fields that represent sets of things. Will be useful for NUMA
topology object which will be added in subsequent patches.

Change-Id: I66d61c760a70ad661dff4c40c6933df06192ee8f
Blueprint: virt-driver-numa-placement

commit_message:
Ensure proper ordering of XML arguments

Random hash ordering can cause the 'encoding' argument to be rendered
in the XML string before the 'version' argument, resulting in XML
deserialization errors on the Keystone side.  This modifies
Document's string rendering to not rely on dict ordering when
constructing the header tag's version + encoding arguments and avoids
XML auth issues when using PYTHONHASHSEED=random.

Change-Id: I66d18a2f8da1088ec5d310a43c84df7e4d6a6f6b

commit_message:
Correclty detected osd when the journal is a file

When the journal of the osd is set to a file instead of a partition,
ceph-disk list report a normal filesystem like this:

 /dev/sda2 other, xfs, mounted on /var/lib/ceph/osd/ceph-5

So we must check that /var/lib/ceph/osd/ceph-5/journal point to
the journal passed to the osd class.

This patch ensure that.

Change-Id: I30ce854337d41029f3863e4cffef76685b8dcc0c

commit_message:
Add cm_api to global requirements

cm_api is needed for this blueprint:
Plugin for CDH with Cloudera Manager
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/sahara/+spec/cdh-plugin

This library will be used by Sahara for provisioning clusters
with Cloudera Hadoop distribution

Licensed by Apache-2.0
This library not compatible with Python 3
Ubuntu and Fedora don't provide packages with cm_api

Partially implement: blueprint cdh-plugin

Change-Id: I638d04d8bcece055e655b4243ad9c0f8d9dd8a70

commit_message:
Use immutable arg rather mutable arg

Passing mutable objects as default args is a known Python pitfall.
We'd better avoid this. This commit changes mutable default args with
None, then use 'arg = arg or []'.

Change-Id: Ib3c6c3dd836255ee2435e3045404a0b3b0b4c534

Right, sorry I see the issue here.  The bash8 check job does not run after a devstack run, it runs separately.  so yes, installing in devstack doesn't help.

Sorry, I was thinking about the case of a person running this after they've run stack.sh

I guess your original virtualenv idea is the quickest solution to this. the thing is other projects run_tests.sh have rather extensive setups for virtualenv's.  maybe we should copy some of that?  i'd like to see at least the same cmd line options as other projects for sanity and not re-creating it if exists (when i've done bigger changes, running bash8 over and over again till you get it right is common)

i guess we can assume python-virtualenv installed, because jenkins can't install it anyway.

should we be pulling git versions of bashate too?  good for testing, but maybe less good for reliability"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-17 03:43:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Verified-1

commit_message:
bashate known as bash8 should be installed from pypi mirror.

bashate is available on pypi mirror,
We can install it from there and use it in run_tests.sh
file. So, bash8.py file is removed from devstack.

Change-Id: Ibf25e2e51a582114aad3c63cea2579f14b29d350
Closes-Bug: #1320535

By the time we try to create the internal bridge on compute and network
nodes, they have already been created, resulting in an error message.

'}]
commit_message:
labs: fix ovs-vsctl error

By the time we try to create the internal bridge on compute and network
nodes, they have already been created, resulting in an error message.

This patch informs ovs-vsctl that the bridge may already exist.

Change-Id: Ib1b951f639d208b98769f28a66d0edff27ae6224

For someone totally unfamiliar with this, can you just explain what glance.store is and why it is separate?

the pypi page isn't very helpful ("Glance's stores library") [1], the readme isn't helpful [2] and googling for "glance.store" doesn't point me at anything useful...

[2] https://github.com/openstack/glance.store/blob/master/README.rst'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2014-08-26 20:29:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@Ian, sorry about that. I'll work on documenting it better.

Glance store is a new library the Image Service program is working on. It contains the code that used to live under `glance/store` which is responsible for managing the stores where Glance stores the data into.

In order to migrate Glance to this library, we need to remove the `glance/store` package from the code base but in order to do that, we need this patch to land as well.

Does the above clears your doubts?

The Glance team has agreed on moving forward with the library and all the necessary patches have been submitted. I believe/hope, this is the last one required outside Glance."}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2014-08-26 20:29:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Install glance.store from git instead of pypi

In order to use python packages, we need to have all packages in a
namespace installed using the same method - either develop or install.
Therefore, we need to override the pip installed glance.store package
with one installed from the git repo.

commit_message:
document VMDK driver support for Cinder block storage

- mention that starting with Fuel 5.1 we support VMDK driver for Cinder
- explicitly state that user has to change Cinder backend after
  finishing environment creation with vCenter as hypervisor option
- update screenshot where user selects storage backends for Cinder and
  Glance, right now there is no choice available, becase currently Ceph
  cannot be used with vCenter
- add screenshot showing where user can change Cinder storage backend
- correct Cinder definition in Terminology reference, that *VMDK*
  driver enables vCenter datastores support, not *vCenter* driver
- remove limitation in Planning guide that tells that VMDK driver is not
  supported, which is not true anymore
- add limitation in Planning guide that the only supported backend for
  Cinder is VMDK driver

Implements: blueprint vcenter-documentation-update-fuel-5.1
Change-Id: Idc2412f2d897d76e68c968bb77b84e350af07cd1

commit_message:
Add recognition of 'INSERT IF NOT EXISTS'

Analyses expected_condition_map in put_item requests
whether 'INSERT IF NOT EXISTS' behavior is expected
and handles it properly

Fixes bug: 1360131

commit_message:
Add two more tests which check workflow execution

- added test that check execution of mixed workflow (Mistral v1)
- added test that check execution of direct workflow where all keywords are used
(on-error, on-success, on-finish)

Implements blueprint: mistral-workflow-execution-tests

Change-Id: I3055d0084a8f8a69bd8ac5cd51e7c5e7ce049b63

commit_message:
Next version of stable/icehouse is 2014.1.1.

pbr pre-versioning causes current sdist of stable/icehouse to have
versions leading up to 2013.2, but that is already released - we
should be leading up to 2014.1.1 in this repository.

Change-Id: If4140a5a439a5ee93566e95c0cecd30ed7eeeea5

So I'm generally for syncing the models with migrations. So much so that my blueprint does the same thing :)

I had originally built my blueprint on top of this one, but after digging deeper into alembic and my implementation, I ended up with a different solution to ensure that the model stays accurate.

Unfortunately the schema comparison code in alembic is incomplete (it ignores constraints for instance). There are other reasons why it's unsuitable for my blueprint as well so I ended up with a new implementation.

My blueprint leverages that code to ensure that the model continues being updated with any migrations.

Maybe a good solution would be to leverage my comparison implementation for this blueprint and I can then make my blueprint dependent on this one?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-16 11:20:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: -Verified

commit_message:
Sync models with migrations.

We are using declarative_base in nova.db.models just for reflection,
not for db creation. For creation we are using migrations. Actual state
of models is not the same as the database state.

The goal of proposed bp is to sync models with migrations, fix mistakes
and add testing of migrations and db models on real backends.

bp db-sync-models-with-migrations

Change-Id: I2545f93618e315547e7bbc346f7ac4aee8134ff9

commit_message:
Fix check-sanity + save-state /w disabled services

This adds a mapping for all process names described in BASE_SERVICES
and TARGET_SERVICES, allowing check-sanity to skip checking for running
processes of services that are disabled according to ENABLED_SERVICES.
It also updates grenade.sh and save-state to only dump databases that
exist.  These changes allow grenade to pass against deployments that
have disabled non-essential services in devstack.

Change-Id: Ic4b2bab88b12f33f939b9bf7aca47e930d799f3f
Closes-bug: #1355499

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

OK, we have to figure this out, because at this point you have 4 reviews open for a single change :)

The first thing I want to check here is that you are using a recent version of "git-review": if I do "sudo pip freeze | grep git-review", I get "git-review==1.23"; if this isn't what you get when you do this command, do "sudo pip install -U git-review".

The second thing I want to check is that you've done "git review -s" in the repository with the most recent version of "git-review": this command installs a "commit-msg" hook, which ensures that a "Change-Id" footer exists on the commit message.  This hook should take care to not overwrite the footer if it already exists.

The final thing is to be sure that you're constructing the footer correctly.  It should be exactly:

    Change-Id: I820d793ac44680295df8b2a3f58a0834f7019875

There should be no spaces before the footer name, and there should be no blank lines after it.  It must be separated from the rest of the text of the commit message by a blank line.  The footer name must be spelled exactly "Change-Id", with the 'C' in 'Change' and the 'I' in 'Id' capitalized.

To be clear, all of the above is trying to correct an automation failure I've never seen before; once we have this sorted out, you shouldn't ever need to worry about Change-Id again, as long as you preserve whatever the hook generates on the first upload.

(While you're at it, please review https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages for guidance on how the commit message itself should be formatted; so far, none of the commit messages you've used have been completely acceptable)'}, {'account_id': 679, 'date': '2014-06-05 20:09:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Sean's -1 just means that he would prefer this not be merged; it doesn't prevent someone else from going ahead and approving the patch over Sean's objections, though in practice that rarely happens.  In this case, I happen to disagree with Sean (partially).  I figure that the best way to think about this kind of -1 is that it is an opportunity to discuss the approach and objections; you might convince Sean of your viewpoint, or you may learn something from his response to your questions.

Now, on to my disagreement with Sean: I agree that the server should implement exactly this sort of check; the server must be the ultimate arbiter of policy.  However, from a user friendliness standpoint, there's no harm in the client duplicating the effort, and it in fact prevents a second round-trip with the server in the event the user made an error in the entry.  I would agree that this deserves a -1 if it were in the API code, but since this is on the CLI side, I think it is entirely appropriate and desirable that the client should try to filter the arguments and alert the user as quickly as possible as to the problem.  That said, I can see that we run the risk of code drift, as this essentially runs afoul of the DRY principle.  I think it is appropriate for a CLI to have a limited amount of repetition, though"}, {'account_id': 11622, 'date': '2014-06-30 19:52:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13:

commit_message:
Adding cornercases for set_metadata

Aggregate_set_metadata leaves users confused because it currently
does not check for duplicate key=value parameters for addition
or a missing key for deletion. All that user sees is that "metadata has been updated"
more details in bug1292572

This patch checks for above mentioned corner cases and informs users when and why
there was no change made in above corner cases

Adding better testcases also.

   Closes-Bug: #1292572

Change-Id: I820d793ac44680295df8b2a3f58a0834f7019875

commit_message:
Source all devstack service libs for Tempest

Devstack's tempest library relies on TEMPEST_SERVICES when
configuring the service_available section of tempest.conf. This
is built as various service libraries are sourced into the environment.
This imports all relevant devstack service libraries to ensure the
services_available section of tempest.conf is accurate.

Change-Id: Iea9c08f5ce374c4343ae56adb49221737c7a55d7

commit_message:
Add within-juno dir and within-master symlink

This adds logic to upgrade_project() to call project upgrade
scripts from the within-$release directory if performing a
sideways upgrade within the same release.  A symlink named
within-master is added and linked to the current development
release to allow sideways migration testing of trunk.  When Juno
tags are cut and K opens, a from-kilo directoy should be created
and this symlink updated.

Change-Id: I770075442d05f38515e5dadf24f2c642d14d7845

commit_message:
Set the python hash seed that tox uses to 0

The current trove unit tests don't work correctly with the random
hash seed that the new tox sets by default.

This change forces the new tox to use 0 as the hash seed which
should unblock the gate until we can fix the trove unit tests
to run correctly with a random hash seed.

This change will probably need to be backported to the stable
branches to ensure that the tox tests keep working there as well.

Change-Id: Ib5c6d4d166c847ce94ec70740c5753d338687865
(cherry picked from commit 7e6cf5bfaf57ef8628c8f72ea29ecd12179fab72)

commit_message:
Catch BadRequest exception from correct module

Catch the correct BadRequest exception from the neutron
client module so deployments that don't support overlapping
IP addresses can be tested.

Change-Id: Ica58ffbff6cedd362e2b2b807438ec61bddf2f25
Closes-Bug: #1359508

commit_message:
Ensure assertion matches dict iter order in test

Fixes a test_linux_ip_lib test that made an assertion
on a command that was called that could fail depending
on the order of the dictionary when it was iterated over.

This patch makes the assertion match the order that the
command is constructed by iterating through the dictionary
as well.

Partial-Bug: #1348818
Change-Id: I7baa518169c193f7e98d38632e1db16eb57ffee7

commit_message:
Add support for provider-network extension in nuage Plugin

This implements support for creating provider networks
with Nuage plugin.

Implements: blueprint providernet-ext-support-for-nuage-plugin
Change-Id: Ibabc1561fc7b6bd5ea38617f145af1d0d4545a4f

commit_message:
Clear entries in Cisco N1KV specific tables on rollback

During rollback operations, resources are cleaned up from neutron
database but leaves a few stale entries in the n1kv specific tables.
This change addresses the proper clean up of tables. i.e. VLAN/VXLAN
allocation tables, profile binding and vm network table.

Conflicts:

        neutron/plugins/cisco/n1kv/n1kv_neutron_plugin.py

Change-Id: I7a09d34f3a9dee0a43b76c5d781ee9eb9938953a
Closes-bug: #1336596
(cherry picked from commit 73b4239fbef5e52494cf3ffc3293dbb79b52d91c)

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-14 18:09:34.000000000', 'message': "Require Class['mysql::server'], not Service['mysqld'] when creating DB.

When using version >= 2.2 of the MySQL module, setting up the database
for Keystone depended on the MySQL service (Service['mysqld']). However,
if the service is not managed by Puppet (e.g. it is managed through
Pacemaker instead), this would cause catalog compilation to fail because
there is no Service['mysqld']. This is the case when the MySQL module is
called with service_manage => false. Requiring Class['mysql::server']
instead fixes this.

commit_message:
Require Class['mysql::server'], not Service['mysqld'] when creating DB.

When using version >= 2.2 of the MySQL module, setting up the database
for Keystone depended on the MySQL service (Service['mysqld']). However,
if the service is not managed by Puppet (e.g. it is managed through
Pacemaker instead), this would cause catalog compilation to fail because
there is no Service['mysqld']. This is the case when the MySQL module is
called with service_manage => false. Requiring Class['mysql::server']
instead fixes this.

Change-Id: I4ba7932d679764576a46ea599499991a5c57fc56
Closes-Bug: 1349316
(cherry picked from commit 5837aaeaadb14fdc089b25e666cfd8d91f0f53a6)

commit_message:
Disable Openstack services startup on install

Upstart makes services went off once installed.
We're wanting them started only then configured.
If ceph is used volumes, leave cinder-volume override
on its own (rbd.pp will configure it).

Closes-bug: #1348185
Closes-bug: #1335804

Change-Id: I50ff5b0f5bc3d80bfef917116a620bd9386e8e56
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

Couple of minor things. the databsae table bothers me, because it'll always be stuck there if we can't rename it. There are ways to deal with the FK/sqlite thing (catch and ignore the errors sqlite throws while dropping FKs) but if everyone's ok with the table name change, i guess i can live with it. 

Alternatively, can we just create a new table and ignore the old one? Or is the data still used to determine the environment state (which is something else I'm not keen on). Ideally the action table would just be a historical record and therefore it wouldn't matter if it got destroyed.

I like the intent behind this in general, though; it will make deletion and error handling much more consistent."}, {'account_id': 7600, 'date': '2014-08-05 15:38:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 26: Code-Review-1

"}, {'created': '2014-06-16 08:06:45.000000000', 'message': "Adds REST API endpoint for action execution

Deployment is replaced with a more generic concept called 'action'.
Action can be performed on any object of Object Model.
Actions are marked with 'Usage: Action' in MuranoPL code. They can have arguments.
List of available actions can be obtained from Object Model itself after initial deployment.
This commit adds ability to REST API invoke actions by providing its unique id (from OM) and parameters.
Also refactors API code to use tasks.
Database table isn't renamed because in MySQL 5.5 this cannot be done without dropping FK constraints
in status table and this operation is not supported by SQLite. SQLite can rename table without errors but FK
constraint becomes invalid pointing to non-existing table. So renaming is done on Model level, not in DB

Change-Id: If21809340bb799af58a8d1a2d148e52565028970
Partially-Implements: blueprint application-actions

commit_message:
Adds REST API endpoint for action execution

Deployment is replaced with a more generic concept called 'action'.
Action can be performed on any object of Object Model.
Actions are marked with 'Usage: Action' in MuranoPL code. They can have arguments.
List of available actions can be obtained from Object Model itself after initial deployment.
This commit adds ability to REST API invoke actions by providing its unique id (from OM) and parameters.
Also refactors API code to use tasks.

Change-Id: If21809340bb799af58a8d1a2d148e52565028970
Partially-Implements: blueprint application-actions

commit_message:
[Hbase] Adds new functions redesigning keys for data storing

Function prepare_key constructs keys with column as separator.
Other methods "quote/unquote" deal with data that is used in keys construction.
Function "quote" exchanges all columns that it finds in getting params.
"unquote" restores getting data for its initial state.

Related-bug: #1328114
Change-Id: I201fbe14e77ce2e7075b60f8fe353a3538d73db6

Catch "Gateway timeout (HTTP 504)" as whole word in provider rather than simple 50[34].

Closes-Bug: 1334306

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary parameter from config

Tenant_isolation parameter is duplicated in Compute and Orchestration
sections of config.py, but according to code it's used only of
Compute section and no sense to define it in other places.

Closes-Bug: #1340380
Change-Id: I198e0f3d8a0f7e2f91ed98f6f7deab90454f993d

commit_message:
Upgrades, handle socket.timeout exception in health checker

It happens not often, but sometimes
when we make http call, it raises
socket.timeout exception.

* handle socket.timeout exception
  in health checker
* also fixed wrong log message
  in health checker

Change-Id: I9f90540a6ea3687b0f9fd640242af02e50c5d484
Closes-bug: #1362508

commit_message:
Convert create_backup v3 plugin to v2.1 API

Changes required to have v3 plugin natively support the V2.1
API

The create_backup action is reverted back to createBackup

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Ibac7eb2644629f4b9cf0581d9859b97f263972c8

commit_message:
Implementing task execution infrastructure

* Implemented action calls
* Implemented subworkflow calls
* Adding executor interface and default implementation
* Unit tests
* Small refactoring in workflow handlers
* Creating all necessary RPC infrastructure
* Refactoring launch script
* Added __repr__() implementation to MistralContext
* Small fixes in old infrastructure

Change-Id: I134ea526c295ca9bda7214c5403a41966062ff79

commit_message:
properly format user guide in RST

The user guide isn't formatted properly for RST. Cosmetically,
the lines are too long and some have extra non-printing characters.
Lists aren't formatted for RST.

This fixes the file so that the lines are no more than 80 characters
wide, removes the non-printing characters, and makes use of
RST-formatting for the lists.

The text itself is not modified.

Change-Id: I8d2f3e4723e619014c056946e4f226d9c0e8f48a
Partial-Bug: #1353688

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Change Log level from ERROR to DEBUG

When adding a subnet interface to router, an interface inside the
router namespace created, and parallely vpn-agent periodically executes process_router,
which checks existense of interface inside the router namesapce,
and if not exists then print error log and call the self.driver.plug,
so changing that log level from error to debug based on parameter check_exit_code.

Change-Id: Ic5e5b07d6cda70fa4a8dc28cf6937cb4b49735a2
Closes-Bug: #1332789

commit_message:
Add dib-lint exclusions

This patch adds exclusions for the indentation and newline
rules in dib-lint.  The indentation exclusion is needed for
files using heredoc and wanting to preserve indentation.
The newline exclusion is added here for consisently treating
all dib-lint rules the same.

Change-Id: Ic8a2164eba3cf99e55473846e3a5fe663a3c1095

commit_message:
labs: exit for invalid syntax

Make osbash exit with an explanation if no option for building VMs (-b),
creating Windows batch scripts (-w), or exporting node VMs (-e) is given
(there is nothing to do).

Change-Id: I2376a792fcd6303c64a21f4378acb15bd99a476f

commit_message:
Return BadRequest instead of UnprocessableEntity for volumes API

Changes exception from UnprocessableEntity to BadRequest when
input validation fails. Also raise BadRequest instead of a nova
exception InvalidParameterValue within the SnapshotController
create method. This is some preparation work to make sharing
unittests between V2.1 and V2 easier.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I5c5b6f9680378d51f7fea054b52b99cd6cbe54b0

commit_message:
Rename 'Configuring' state to 'Ready to deploy'

'Configuring' is a confusing state since it implies
that some process is running on the background.
But that is not true.
Status 'ready to deploy' indicates that deployment has not been started,
but ready to begin after corresponding button will be pushed

Change-Id: Ia3f0c9036aa989c974fb64563984324ace7bea41
Closes-Bug: #1357220

commit_message:
enable nova v3 scenario tests for server ops, minimum and snapshot

this enables nova v3 scenario tests for test_server_advanced_ops,
test_server_basic_ops, test_minimum_basic, test_snapshot_pattern

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: I87494d7dc5c7b2464d7634d86469e206cc9d43fd

Remove schema loader since all schemas are ported to .py files.

commit_message:
Convert multinic v3 plugin to v2.1

Changes required to have v3 plugin natively support
the v2.1 API.

add_fixed_ip -> addFixedIp
remove_fixed_ip -> removeFixedIp

Removes v3 version of the multinic test and changes to
share use of the v2 unittests code. Backports a v2.1 specific
test.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Ie01eddf1e772092c291b1475404f87e6e6f47c71

commit_message:
Backport v3 multinic tests to v2

Adds tests which were only added to the v3 version of the multinic
unittests. Also renames oddly named test file. This is prep work
for a follow patch to share unittests between v2 and v2.1

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I87ad4d7bfb2f65f60d812dbe29866f28f776145f

commit_message:
Make L3RpcCallback a separate callback class

RPC has a version of itself. In Neutron a plugin implements
several RPC interface, so a single RPC version doesn't work.
In Mixin callback class approach, RPC versioning depends on
each plugin implementation and it makes harder to maintain
RPC version appropriately. This patch series replaces mixin
RPC callback of server side with a separate class.

This commit handles server-side callback of L3-agent RPC interface.
L3-agent server-side callback class is moved from db/ to
api/rpc/handlers because it doesn't involve any db operations
and defining all RPC interfaces in a single place sounds reasonable.

Note that moving other L3-agent related RPC interface class
to api/rpc/handlers will be done in a separate patch as this patch
focuses on reorganizing the server-side RPC callback class.

Partial-Bug: #1359416
Change-Id: Ie3f2c9b2ad907a1110e05fe94d42e41e93fbcaa7

RPC has a version of itself. In Neutron a plugin implements
several RPC interface, so a single RPC version doesn't work.
In Mixin callback class approach, RPC versioning depends on
each plugin implementation and it makes harder to maintain
RPC version appropriately. This patch series replaces mixin
RPC callback of server side with a separate class.

This commit handles server-side callback of security group
RPC interface.
* The server-side callback of Security group RPC is moved to
  api/rpc/handler and db/securitygroups_rpc_base now only
  contains a mixin class to add agent-based security group
  implementation with db operations.
* get_port_from_device method in server-side callback class
  is moved to a mixin class of plugin implementation
  (SecurityGroupServerRpcMixin) because it involves DB lookup
  and is tightly coupled with plugin implementation rather
  than RPC interface definition.

The following items will be planned in later patches
to avoid drastic changes in a single patch.

commit_message:
Make SecurityGroupsRpcCallback a separate callback class

RPC has a version of itself. In Neutron a plugin implements
several RPC interface, so a single RPC version doesn't work.
In Mixin callback class approach, RPC versioning depends on
each plugin implementation and it makes harder to maintain
RPC version appropriately. This patch series replaces mixin
RPC callback of server side with a separate class.

This commit handles server-side callback of security group
RPC interface.
* The server-side callback of Security group RPC is moved to
  api/rpc/handler and db/securitygroups_rpc_base now only
  contains a mixin class to add agent-based security group
  implementation with db operations.
* get_port_from_device method in server-side callback class
  is moved to a mixin class of plugin implementation
  (SecurityGroupServerRpcMixin) because it involves DB lookup
  and is tightly coupled with plugin implementation rather
  than RPC interface definition.

The following items will be planned in later patches
to avoid drastic changes in a single patch.
* Merge security group RPC API and agent callback classes in
  agent/securitygroups_rpc into api/rpc/handlers/securitygroup_rpc
* Remove completely duplicated db access code in get_port_from_device
  and get_port_and_sgs

Partial-Bug: #1359416
Change-Id: Ia6535217d2e3b849a95667c1b53dd09675002892

Move get_port_from_device from RPC callback to plugin mixin

Change-Id: I784cb203eb09286f7677c93032fe6288656d9b10

commit_message:
Add Ironic-python-agent support to devstack-gate

IPA is now upstreamed and needs gate jobs running. This adds support
needed to run gate jobs.

Change-Id: I1cbb2f09b10dd36fbd40e9a20d0ddabdfa1e1192

commit_message:
Minor refactoring for add_router_to_l3_agent

This method is more complicated than it needs
to be, and it makes it difficult to target
fixes for it.

Furthermore, this method calls into
auto_schedule_routers, which duplicates some
of the DB calls already made in the above
mentioned method. This refactoring
is done in preparation of the performance
improvement.

Partial-bug: #1356121
Related-Bug: #1358636

Change-Id: I9a0cfa41a5f067949b964d39157def55c40bf9af

commit_message:
Revert "Remove docutils pin"

This reverts commit c89fc517f19ed2c631434cccd378d2e80f7cc42a.
The previous change of all repos missed all the specs repositories that contained also a docutils pin.
Patches for *-specs repositories will get generated now with ID I9107884d964757a9154bdd1feb4ea6df4e9df43e.

Change-Id: I7eae1b50cc48b00eb62ab7667cec7bddf9916611

for router create.

--distributed=false.

commit_message:
Fixes a CLI issue with the DVR

Allows to set the distributed flag for
DVR.

--distributed=True and --distributed=False
for router create.

The current patch set allows admins to
create_router with --distributed=True and
--'distributed=False.

Partially-implements: blueprint neutron-ovs-dvr
Closes-Bug: #1347960

Change-Id: I37fbd321ccb184c8d8349122c7326951f8494b52

commit_message:
Predictable iptables chains output order

This fixes the iptables unit tests that break with a randomized PYTHONHASHSEED
(see the bug report).

The chains for iptables are stored as sets to avoid duplicates. When they are
output by iptables_manager their order can therefore be unpredictable. This was
found hash seed 1016732220.

To fix this we:
 - Sort the chains output by iptables_manager
 - Update the unit tests to check for sorted chains

When multiple tables are processed, they can be processed in any order or
dumped in any order. Found with hash seed 3728666619.

To fix this we:
 - Traverse the tables in sorted order for dumping
 - Fix tests to allow for tables to be processed in any order

Note: There are several other unrelated unit tests that also break with a
randomized PYTHONHASHSEED, but they are not addressed here. They will be
addressed in separate patches.

Partial-bug: #1348818

Change-Id: Ic3f4cd85316c9fc2e78bc7f5e900cfac87baf39d

commit_message:
Cherry pick oslo rpc HA fixes

Get 2 commits from oslo-rpc fixing HA failover:
* Ia148baa6e1ec632789ac3621c85173c2c16f3918 (fixed HA failover, Qpid
 part)
* I67923cb024bbd143edc8edccf35b9b400df31eb3 (fixed HA failover, RabbitMQ
 part)
Closes-Bug: #1261631

Change-Id: I154a1e4230cf956e0d6a71a8e717866d0cd17a12

[{'created': '2014-01-08 14:35:06.000000000', 'message': 'Filters: Adds ability to configure max_instances_per_host from aggregates

Is now possible to use the filter AggregateNumInstancesFilter and
define an aggregate with a metadata "max_instances_per_host" to
configure the max instances can be hosted by hosts.

  + Creates new filter AggregateNumInstancesFilter
  + Adds a base class for NumInstancesFilter
  + Updates devrefs for: NumInstancesFilter and AggregateNumInstancesFilter
  + Adds unit tests for AggregateNumInstancesFilter

Note:
  This upgrade was largely inspired from AggregateRamFilter
  and AggregateCoreFilter.

DocImpact

commit_message:
filter: add per-aggregate filter to configure max_instances_per_host

Adds a filter AggregateIoOpsFilter which provides the ability
to read from aggregates metadata "max_instances_per_host".

DocImpact
Implements: blueprint per-aggregate-max-instances-per-host
Change-Id: I569aab7842d2c67042b89c75941a4664a599a7f6

commit_message:
Remove sahara-dashboard installation

Sahara dashboard is now merged into the Horizon and enabled by default
(when data_processing endpoint is available), so, we should stop
installing it as separated dashboard.

Change-Id: I5636e9f51fb3072c30407032a6346b391c288a2c

Remove docutils pin

This was added to work around bug 1091333.  A new sphinx has been
released and so this is no longer necessary.

nit: Comments added.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-08-26 17:54:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

With this change it seems like I can no longer do:

neutron router-create test1 --distributed

In the past I could omit the bool value; now I am required to pass a Flag, either True or False.

Even though the help message:

neutron router-create [-h] [-f {shell,table,value}] [-c COLUMN]
                             [--max-width <integer>] [--prefix PREFIX]
                             [--request-format {json,xml}]
                             [--tenant-id TENANT_ID] [--admin-state-down]
                             [--distributed {True,False}]
                             NAME

Seems clear about this I wonder if we should document this behavior regression.'}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2014-08-26 18:05:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

The official documentation is per-release, not for trunk chasers. Or were you thinking of another form of documentation?'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-08-26 18:06:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

IMO, a DocImpact on the commit message, with a description of the change in behavior would suffice.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-08-26 18:08:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

but that said, is there any way we can keep the old behavior?'}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2014-08-26 19:42:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)

I spent some time on this and I don't think it's possible with how the client is currently designed."}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2014-08-26 19:46:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2014-08-26 19:50:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2014-08-26 20:29:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I'm embarrassed to say that I didn't realize that --distributed would no longer work without an explicit True or False argument.  That seems pretty annoying.  Let me play with this a bit and think about it.  Incidentally, I did my testing by explicitly passing True and False because at the time that was what I was interested in seeing.

Thanks for pointing that out, Armando.  Sorry to Assaf for the oversight.  I'll get back to this."}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2014-08-26 21:02:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

The fact that this command is admin-only takes the sting out of it a little bit.  Still thinking...'}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2014-08-26 21:09:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I don't understand why any of this matters. The client has had a release with the previous behavior, sure, but Neutron itself hasn't obviously. I'm assuming we don't care about trunk chasers here because trunk chasers are very much used to behavior changes mid-cycle. The help text explains how the flag should be used and this is consistent with how the rest of the Neutron CLI works. If you want to be able to specify False then you have two options:

--distributed=True/False
--distributed / --non-distributed (Or similar).

The client, as far as I know, has no option 3."}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2014-08-26 22:06:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2

I was just hoping that --distributed could be a synonym for --distributed=True.  So, I had to go convince myself that it won't be possible to do get that in a reasonable way.  This is okay.  The behavior with this patch is an improvement in others ways."}, {'account_id': 7016, 'date': '2014-08-26 23:19:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Also with the choices, you have to type in with the right case, otherwise it will error out.
Would it make sense to add choices that would support both upper and lower case."true", "True", "false'. 'False''}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-08-26 23:29:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Assaf, I think here we're just saying that there's a slight change of behavior, and we wanna make sure that's captured somehow, if we are unable to reasonably make sure we preserve the existing behavior.

We don't want people to file bugs of the likes 'neutron router-create --distributed' no longer works, this commit message broke it! Assaf: it's your fault! :)"}, {'account_id': 1923, 'date': '2014-08-26 23:36:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-27 00:52:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

commit_message:
Fix CLI support for DVR, take 2

Previously --distributed was displayed as positional
argument in the help text, but acted as an optional
argument with the -- semantics. It now behaves like
any other optional argument.

A side-effect is that previously you could:
1) neutron router-create --distributed r1
2) neutron router-create --distributed=True r1
3) neutron router-create --distributed=False r1

While now only options 2 and 3 are viable.

DocImpact
Partially-implements: blueprint neutron-ovs-dvr
Closes-Bug: #1346121
Change-Id: I60675b4f60fe8154af4ab6d8f0e93867cf362a59

commit_message:
Prefer "val !=/== ref" over "val (not) in [ref]" in conditions

This change increases readibility with the following replacements in
conditions:

 * val in [ref] ==> val == ref
 * val not in [ref] ==> val != ref

Change-Id: I52a77aff60c8e46fa5f6290e3a565f58425d9a68

commit_message:
Fix some of tests that rely on hash ordering

With tox 1.7.2 hash randomization will be on by default, causing
random failures of tests. How to reproduce:
* Update tox
* Remove "PYTHONHASHSEED=0" from tox.ini
* Run something like:
  $ for i in {1..20}; do tox -epy27 || break; done

Changes:
* Made most of generated stuff predictable by adding sorting

Not done:
* Current API validation checks nothing relying on specific response for
  specific hash. I tried to test it based on regexp patterns but it
  looks like more discussion is needed. See
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/112736/ for more details. This patch
  is a part that can be done without regexps.

Change-Id: I92a714cf9c29547e875170547a6c0625ddaebc88
Partial-Bug: #1348818

commit_message:
Create RemoteFSSnapDriver class

Move RemoteFSDriver into its own file.

Refactor pieces needed for qcow2 snapshots into a class.

Also add self.SHARE_FORMAT_REGEX.

Implements bp: remotefs-snaps

Change-Id: I8f9eaed125f4b916b835a63b04239058e34492a9

commit_message:
Filter out registered nodes with ironic

As a first step to making register-nodes idempotent, also filter
out nodes that are registered with ironic before performing node
registration.

Change-Id: Ia0f5eaf2728cc2caf7f59546d226ddc6bd337b77

commit_message:
Permit usage of notifications for metering

This patch introduces a new publisher that uses notification instead
of RPC.

And set it by default.

Closes bug: #1005933
Implements blueprint replace-rpc-cast-with-notifications
Co-Authored-By: Ala Rezmerita <ala.rezmerita@cloudwatt.com>

Change-Id: Idc40c148ef60d5e1349d30c66ba85691d93c5675

'}, {'created': '2014-08-20 13:09:51.000000000', 'message': 'Fix for LBaaS VIP Ports to be serviced by DVR

Currently, DVR router namespaces are created only
when there is a valid VM port on the compute
node, or for the gateway-port on the service node.
But when an LBaaS VIP port is created the l3 agent
does not create a DVR namespace to service the VIP port.
This fix enables DVR namespaces to be created to
service the LBaaS VIP port.

Also, this fix enables L2 Agent running in DVR
mode, to add-in OVS rules to enable packets to
be routed to such LBaaS VIP Ports which are
resident on DVR routed interfaces.

Therefore, with this fix both East-West and
North-South traffic will be serviced by DVR
for LBaas VIP Ports.

Change-Id: I698b971d50721fb0512a11569f7d3139d0d456f3
Closes-Bug: #1356464

commit_message:
Fix DVR to service LBaaS VIP Ports

Currently, DVR router namespaces are created only
when there is a valid VM port on the compute
node, or for the gateway-port on the service node.
But when an LBaaS VIP port is created the l3 agent
does not create a DVR namespace to service the VIP port.
This fix enables DVR namespaces to be created to
service the LBaaS VIP port.

Also, this fix enables L2 Agent running in DVR
mode, to add-in OVS rules to enable packets to
be routed to such LBaaS VIP Ports which are
resident on DVR routed interfaces.

Therefore, with this fix both East-West and
North-South traffic will be serviced by DVR
for LBaas VIP Ports.

DocImpact

Authored-by: Swaminathan Vasudevan <swaminathan.vasudevan@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Vivekanandan Narasimhan <vivekanandan.narasimhan@hp.com>

Change-Id: I698b971d50721fb0512a11569f7d3139d0d456f3
Closes-Bug: #1356464

moving out of the incubator into a library, so projects that wish to

commit_message:
Add oslo.serialization

Add the new Oslo library for managing object serialization. This code is
moving out of the incubator into a library, so projects that wish to
continue using it need the requirement added to the global list first.

Change-Id: Iff29ce2e88cddc2332229cfbbc518251dd2c76f3

Remove hash seed dependency for unittests

latest tox has random hash seed enabled, that causes
unstable unittests errors.

I am not convinced this should be an ISE (internal server error) instead of a 401. My justification for questioning this is that if Keystone is raising a 500 back to Nova (for example) the middleware was in-fact unable to validate the token, which in turn should be an unauthorized error.

Basically, can't validate (regardless of why keystone couldn't validate) is an auth error not a 500 in Nova or the consuming service.

The 500 indicates that Nova had an internal (unhandled) error, but in fact it simply can't validate the token (which legitimately is a 401 in all other cases)."}, {'account_id': 11428, 'date': '2014-07-15 09:12:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Correct return code

When a nova-api call is made with a token, the middleware
verifies the token with keystone. Even if the response from
keystone is an internal error the response shown to user is
401 (unauthorised). Checked the return code in verify_uuid_token()
and raised an exception and then caught it in _validate_user_token()
and then raised an ServiceError exception.

Closes bug: #1112167

Change-Id: I84d8db6d277720d5a81fd16f0027b0309862b80f

commit_message:
One Convergence: Skip all tests with 'v6' in name

Adds a check to the test setup for the One Convergence tests
to look for v6 in the name of the test and skip it if present.
This prevents IPv6 developers from having to explicitly skip
each new IPv6 test in the One Convergence unit tests until the
plugin gains IPv6 support.

Closes-bug: #1361366
Change-Id: I5c17d7290302597d5c85ef2c1df95f4f71e1a69b

XenAPI support: List the instances

1) Added XenAPI inspector.
2) Implemented inspect_instances() to list the instances on the XenServer host.

commit_message:
Copy pbr/tools/integration.sh to the requirements repo

The requirements repository is where the integration test is run
from, this is a copy of the pbr integration.sh script to the
repository that actually does the work for validating updates to
the OpenStack global requirements. Housing this script outside
of the requirements repository is a little bit odd.

Once the script is relocated to the requirements repository the
gate and check jobs can start referencing the new location.

Change-Id: Ie1d8415bbfb0c2148352dd7fd61f774ff1502003

commit_message:
Fix creation of cifs entry in cmode driver

Cmode driver tries to create NetBIOS name in cifs server and fails, because
this name should be unique, but driver did not use unique value for it.
Also removed silent passing when cifs entry was not created.

Change-Id: Ic05c7a0d2e6c544d06eb5f1e255c21083e5e6938
Closes-Bug: #1356387
Closes-Bug: #1356395

subject: Updated documentation of "DummyProvider to "ExistingServers"
revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-27 23:50:48.000000000', 'message': 'Updated documentation of "DummyProvider to "ExistingServers"

ExistingServers replaced DummyProvider in code
a while ago, but documentation was not updated to reflect
the change until now.

commit_message:
Updated documentation of "DummyProvider to "ExistingServers"

ExistingServers replaced DummyProvider in code
a while ago, but documentation was not updated to reflect
the change until now.

Change-Id: I3a302e7724601a2f11e6889dd6f207b82581e20f

commit_message:
Support reserving ips at network create time

It is horribly inefficient to create a network and reserve a large
swath of ips, so allow the network creator to specify which ips
he wants to be available in the network by specifying allowed_start
and allowed_end.

Something like:

network-create foo --cidr 10.0.0.0/24 --allowed-start 10.0.0.5 \
    --allowed-end 10.0.0.250

would ensure that 10.0.0.0-10.0.0.4 and 10.0.0.254-10.0.0.255 are
marked reserved so instances would be assigned addresses from the
middle of the range.

Partially-implements blueprint better-support-for-multiple-networks

Change-Id: I5427e1a2d202658d374292559fc7054f2fa51124

the change until now.

commit_message:
ext-gw update on dvr router improperly handled by l3-agent

The recently added external_gateway method does not check
the agent mode or host binding before adding an external
gateway to a particular node/agent.  This fix adds the
required checks in the update path.

Change-Id: Idbb76eea1faec1c5d6b7615d23d74760cc327bb2
Closes-bug: #1356734

commit_message:
Fixes Neutron configuration

Fixes configuration for interface_driver. The driver configured was
nova.networklinux_net.LinuxOVSInterfaceDriver which is for flat
networks. In our labs cluster we are supporting L3 layer
functionality which is provided by
neutron.agent.linux.interface.OVSInterfaceDriver.

Change-Id: I71d971a27afea377e27eb8acbb46d283a62b5aa3

commit_message:
Expand baremetal nodes coverage `POST`

Expand `POST` tests for create baremetal nodes API:
    - expand post tests
    - added negative post tests
    - added parameters for Ironic's admin API which driver to use
      in config

Change-Id: I3172601a063a106a81103e6e55592727014f064c

commit_message:
Add sh as a requirement

sh module is an interface to use subprocess. It would allow us to
easily call any program as if it were a function

Our first use would be in solum, to use git in python code, instead
of having complicated subprocess call for each git command

sh is available on pypi here https://pypi.python.org/pypi/sh
documentations & examples http://amoffat.github.io/sh/

Change-Id: If8b34ed1ffa4cdd57ef3e60dfb964ae244436ddd

commit_message:
Garbage collect neutron ports not in nw_cache

This patch adds code which garbage collects ports in neutron that are
not found in nova's network cache and should be deleted. These ports
usually manifest when nova-compute fails to receive a response from neutron
when creating a port due to a timeout. This patch unfortunately needs to wrap
allocate_for_instance in @synchronized() in order to prevent a
possible race condition when hotplugging a network-interface to an instance
and the port is garbage collected before its put into the network_cache.

Closes-bug: #1324934

Change-Id: I1435b73756fe8f0702e2377a486e0a75ff0480bc

commit_message:
Adds support to set admin password from the cli

The API already supports this feature. This should be used as
nova boot --image <image> --flavor <flavor> --admin-pass <pass> vm-name

However, not all hypervisors support this

Change-Id: I1177e3b2a9284f62b061b7d806f0754a59d8cb5f
Closes-Bug: #1248517
DocImpact

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-02-26 14:24:04.000000000', 'message': 'Clean up _from_db_object() in object models to reuse the base one

There are a lot of places where _from_db_object() functions are the same,
for example, dns_domain, instance_action, instance_event, instance_fault,
instance_info_cache, keypair, migration, security_group, and virtual_interface.

For others, though their implementations of _from_db_object() are a bit
different, they are able to reuse some common function defined in the base
class, and add their own specific differences.

The patch is to clean up the redundancies and make the code clean by moving
the generic implementation of _from_db_object() to the base class, and either
calling it in different implementations in the sub-classes or inheriting it
from the base class in the sub-classes.

Related to blueprint icehouse-objects.

Change-Id: Iac144b3e4563bc79eda439ce7f218218ac530c66

'}, {'created': '2014-03-03 06:49:32.000000000', 'message': 'Clean up _from_db_object() in object models to reuse the base one

There are a lot of places where _from_db_object() functions are the same,
for example, dns_domain, instance_action, instance_event, instance_fault,
instance_info_cache, keypair, migration, security_group, and virtual_interface.

For others, though their implementations of _from_db_object() are a bit
different, they are able to reuse some common function defined in the base
class, and add their own specific differences.

The patch is to clean up the redundancies and make the code clean by moving
the generic implementation of _from_db_object() to the base class, and either

commit_message:
Clean up _from_db_object() in object models to reuse the base one

There are a lot of places where _from_db_object() functions are the same,
for example, dns_domain, instance_action, instance_event, instance_fault,
instance_info_cache, keypair, migration, security_group, and virtual_interface.

For others, though their implementations of _from_db_object() are a little bit
different, they are able to reuse some common function defined in the base
class, and add their own specific differences.

The patch is to clean up the redundancies and make the code clean by moving
the generic implementation of _from_db_object() to the base class, and either
calling it in different implementations in the sub-classes or inheriting it
from the base class in the sub-classes.

Change-Id: Iac144b3e4563bc79eda439ce7f218218ac530c66

commit_message:
Refactors cleanup resource for scenario

Eliminate duplicate code with some refactor using _status_timeout to wait for
resource deletion, which includes a possibility to choose which method to call
trying to get object status, since security group rules doesn't implement it,
preventing us to know if it's deleted or not.
Also removes a hardcoded 10 seconds timeout using CONF.compute.build_interval
instead. This fixes the bug mentioned below.

Fixes bug #1276781

Change-Id: I5711edfd563d55a86238291edc127c0a062dbbf3

What is the downside of this? Is a particular project second class just because it's in Stackforge? I am failing to understand how this is any different than any other project on pypi. Don't think of Mistral as a Stackforge project. Think of it as a pypi library. That's how we are using it.

> Doing this kind of stackforge coupling here means that 
> now solum and mistral are an atomic unit to come forward
> for incubation (should either care to).

No, we only have a dependency on the pypi version of the mistral client. If Mistral wants to file for incubation, that does not mean that Solum needs to.

We need to rely on *some* workflow service. Would you prefer that we use Celery or Spiff workflow? Would you prefer that we copy the python-mistralclient code into our code base?

> I realistically think stackforge projects should be
> removed from projects.txt. 

We are benefiting significantly form running on the same set of requirements as OpenStack. If we were an incubated project, would that mean we would be prohibited from using Mistral because that project is not incubated. Why can we add random pypi projects, and not other Stackforge projects? This seems like a rather serious double standard.

> I'm fine if there is some alternative to g-r for 
> stackforgey things, but I *really* don't like a new 
> requirement being proposed first by a stackforge project.

If other projects use python-mistralclient, why is that bad? How is that any worse than someone asking for spiff workflow?

Sean I think brings up two, unrelated issues:

1) Is the question of mistral being in stackforge. I don't think that really means anything, since we can still evalutate it on the same basis as every other PyPI project.

2) Is the fact that Solum is in stackforge, and should we add new things to global-requirements for things in stackforge.

The answer to (2) comes down to "what global-requirements" is for. If it's just a list of any package someones wanted which passes a certain set of tests (license, py3k, maintaince, etc.), then sure, why not add it? On the other hand, if it's supposed to be something more "official", like the reccomended set of libraries or something, I can see the concern.

That said, I think there needs to be /some/ way for stackforge projects to be able to use libraries that aren't on the list, but still get version upgrades for the rest of their dependencies. Either they need to be able to add them to global-requirements.txt, or there needs to be some other process.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-06-30 22:28:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

"Is a particular project second class just because it's in Stackforge?"

Yes. That's actually the whole point of stackforge, second class citizens that can take advantage of our infrastructure when it doesn't get in the way with the integrated release. Changing our requirements process feels like getting in the way.

I'm entirely happy to take this to the dev list. I really don't think we should be doing stackforge only things in requirements.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-08-27 22:31:53.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

commit_message:
Add python-mistralclient to requirements

Solum is adding new features that allow for user customizable CI
pipelines. Our first implementation uses mistral as the workflow
service. Note that stackforge/solum is currently listed in
projects.txt, and would like to remain there for two key reasons:

1) To use the same set of requirements of OpenStack distributions.
2) To benefit form the automated Jenkins bot reviews as requirements
change.

Solum is deeply integrated with a number of OpenStack services, so
it's critically important to our success to be closely aligned on
requirements. We are reluctant to implement our own workflow service
when one already exists in the stackforge community.

Other alternatives were explored. For reference, see:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-June/038609.html

Change-Id: I6bcf796d9b62aa34bd5017ae6775a050e5c712af

commit_message:
Cleanup of grenade and old/new log copy

This change consolidates the "old" and "new" parts of the log-copy
process into a more consise flow.

Variables OLD_LOG_TARGET and NEW_LOG_TARGET (rename from non-standard
NEWLOGTARGET) are introducted.  The devstack log copy process is
considiated into one block rather than two separate parts.  After
that, several areas that were individually copying parts from the old
and new source tree are combined into one looped copy of a single
canoncial variable EXTRA_COPY

Change-Id: Iddf99555db06d8396c4111a3d77438f904643801

commit_message:
Use /usr/bin/env python instead of /usr/bin/python

The usage of /usr/bin/env ensures that the first interpreter
found in the environment's $PATH variable is used. This should
be preferred.

Change-Id: Ifca0c47f2d1b123b4d5f9fb5e98191262ed25bca

commit_message:
Get meters query performance improvements using index.

Added a index for meter_id and resource_id on the sample table
This gives a 9x performance improvements for mysql v5.5 and 2.58x
improvement for Mysql v5.6.

Add a filter filter on the sub-query when project-id or resource-id
filters are specified in the input.

Closes-Bug: #1320257

Change-Id: I562046f8f0b49e199df63db08eb57cdc46aca73c

commit_message:
Check default parameter value

Default parameter value should not be mutable object, otherwise,
it will be wrong when method is called repeatly and that parameter
is modified in function.

Change-Id: I39127899d5da4866f3f4caa9bd41a586daf2b0f8
see: http://python.net/~goodger/projects/pycon/2007/idiomatic/handout.html#default-parameter-values
Closes-Bug: #1334542

commit_message:
Add "locked" state to Extended Status output

Consumers of the Nova API would like to occasionally see whether
or not an instance has been locked via "nova lock".  Expose this
attribute via Extended Status

Closes-Bug: 1326553
Change-Id: Ida201aca04a2b4d445297f41c91f43a3f726a74e

[{'created': '2014-08-18 15:42:39.000000000', 'message': 'Save base and target release state correctly

If there are both a neutron and neutron_ml2 database, saving state
would fail in both save-state and grenade.sh.

neutron databases were being saved to BASE not TARGET_RELEASE
in grenade.sh

ceilometer databases were not being saved in grenade.sh
